<HEAD>Vietnam Protests Forced Repatriation of Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> told <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> that it rejects the forced repatriation of refugees from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and reserved the right to send them back to the British colony, official Vietnamese media reported Friday. A Foreign Ministry official handed a note on the issue to <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> <PERSON> Emrys </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, said a <ORGANIZATION> Vietnam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> report in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. A group of 51 Vietnamese were flown from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> on Tuesday in the first repatriation of boat people against their will. However, Vietnamese authorities accepted the group back and the official media said without clear explanation that the repatriation was `` part of the framework'' of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s policy of rejecting forced repatriation. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Vietnam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> note strongly affirmed the policy of rejecting forced repatriation and `` and only accepting those who volunteer to return or who are not opposed to the repatriation.'' It said the ministry official cautioned <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> that `` any violation of these principles may hamper and even completely disrupt the process of cooperation to resolve this problem step by step'' as agreed to at the multilateral conference on Indochinese refugees held in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in June. The agency said the ministry official stressed that `` if <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> discovers any case of ` forced repatriation,' it reserves the right to return them to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>.'' Many of the 44,000 Vietnamese who have sailed into <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> since June 1988 are considered illegal `` economic migrants'' unless they can prove they fled their Communist homeland fearing persecution. Thousands have held demonstrations to protest the decision by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> its colony to force the return of the refugees, a decision condemned by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
