<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos-Murders     12-15 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos-Murders,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Knew of Conspiracy That Led to Murders, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> had `` full knowledge'' of an intelligence conspiracy that led to the 1981 murders of two anti-Marcos activists in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, a lawyer told jurors Thursday. But a defense attorney said that although it's easy to see the late <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> dictator as `` the personification of excess and evil,'' no evidence indicates the deaths of Silme Domingo and <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Viernes </PERSON> were caused by anything other than a local union dispute. The lawyers' comments came during closing arguments in a civil lawsuit accusing <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, his widow, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, and others of running an intelligence network that harassed and intimidated anti-Marcos elements in this country. Plaintiffs claim defendant Dr. <PERSON> Leonilo </PERSON> <PERSON> Malabed </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> ran an intelligence slush fund for <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> that paid for the murders, and that the payoff was delivered to the killers by defendant <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Baruso </PERSON>, who was president of the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cannery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Viernes </PERSON>, who were reformist officers of the union, were shot in its offices on June 1, 1981. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' intelligence network `` ran amok'' and <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> did nothing to stop it, plaintiffs' attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Withey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> `` had full knowledge of the conspiracy and not only foresaw but condoned acts of harassment and physical violence'' against his opponents in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Withey </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> court </ORGANIZATION> jury that is hearing the case against the <ORGANIZATION> Marcoses </ORGANIZATION>. Judge <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothstein </PERSON> will judge the liability of five other defendants in the lawsuit, which seeks millions of dollars in damages for the victims' survivors. <PERSON> Withey </PERSON> said the murders were `` made to look like a union dispute _ hot-headed Filipinos shooting it out, vicious thuggery.'' But evidence clearly showed <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> headed an extensive intelligence network not only in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> but in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said. `` We're talking about so many spy agencies you ca n't even count them all,'' <PERSON> Withey </PERSON> said. At the start of the trial Thanksgiving week, <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> defense lawyer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hibey </PERSON> had painted <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Viernes </PERSON> as small fry in the anti-Marcos movement, laboring in `` a smaller vineyard'' than more prominent activists. But <PERSON> Withey </PERSON> noted <PERSON> Viernes </PERSON> had traveled to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> to meet with `` the largest and most threatening labor organization <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> had ever encountered,'' and that both men had sponsored a resolution critical of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> at a <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> labor convention. `` Mr. <PERSON> Hibey </PERSON> may have thought the vineyard was small, but <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> knew better,'' <PERSON> Withey </PERSON> said. Three men linked to a Filipino gang were convicted of murder on the theory that <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Viernes </PERSON> were victims of an internal union dispute over work assignments and gambling in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> fish canneries. `` There was turmoil in this union. There were bribes, there was violence, there were gangs, there was murder,'' <PERSON> Hibey </PERSON> said. `` Sure, it's easy to look upon <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> and <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> as the personification of excess and evil. That's what the case panders to,'' he said. `` Do n't be so blinded by it to seize on the target of two incredibly unpopular people and hold them accountable for that which is not theirs to account.'' But <PERSON> Withey </PERSON> said evidence did n't support that explanation. `` The evidence establishes that <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Viernes </PERSON> were far more than anti-Marcos activists who happened to be killed in an unrelated dispute,'' he said. `` They were very active and effective anti-Marcos activists.'' The jurors must decide whether the Marcoses were part of a conspiracy that led to the murders and whether they were negligent in exercising control over their intelligence network. <PERSON> Rothstein </PERSON> on Thursday granted a motion by the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> government to be dismissed from the suit. In a videotaped deposition made before his death last September, <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, who was overthrown in February 1986, took the Fifth Amendment privilege against self-incrimination when asked about his connections with <PERSON> Malabed </PERSON>.
