<SECOND>AM-Jobs-Graduates,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Job Market Survey Shows Good Growth for College Grads Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 College graduates in 1990 can look forward to a job market much like 1989's _ a year of good growth _ with engineering students pulling in the highest starting salaries, according to an annual survey released Thursday. But the author of the survey said the 260 businesses surveyed were more cautious in their economic outlook than they were a year ago, with 44 percent saying they expected business to be about the same and 6 percent predicting a decline. Fifty percent said they expected a slightly better business climate in 1990. `` This is a rather unusual balance _ a decidedly mixed outlook,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindquist </PERSON>, author of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> Lindquist-Endicott Report of 1990. `` Although there appears to be economic stability with limited growth, there is vulnerability in the marketplace,'' said <PERSON> Lindquist </PERSON>, associate dean and director of placement at the school. `` If a decline in business becomes pronounced and widespread, there will be an immediate and sudden drop in job opportunities for college graduates.'' The 44th annual Lindquist-Endicott report surveyed medium to large businesses and industrial companies. Among those surveyed were major employers in banking, finance, merchandising, electronics and public utilities. <PERSON> Lindquist </PERSON> said there is `` a rather good match'' this year between the number of students entering the job market and the jobs available. But he predicted by 1992 there will be more jobs than students, because of a declining pool of students. He said that on average, starting salaries for this spring's graduates would be up 3.9 percent over last spring, lagging slightly behind inflation But he noted a new trend in which 24 percent of businesses offered signing bonuses of about $ 3,000 on average to students who actually accept jobs. Students with engineering degrees can expect to earn an average $ 32,304 starting salary, the highest among their peers, the report said. Those majoring in computer sciences and chemistry are not far behind, with average starting salaries of $ 29,100 and $ 29,088, respectively. <PERSON> Linquist </PERSON> said the outlook should continue to be strong for computer science majors. Accounting majors got the biggest percentage salary increase, up 5.8 percent over last year's figure to an average of $ 27,408, while starting salaries in sales-marketing showed the smallest increase, up .2 percent to $ 27,828. <PERSON> Lindquist </PERSON> said companies are spending more money recruiting at colleges and universities and noted `` a little bit of craziness'' in which some companies hold college receptions complete with `` caviar, shrimp and exotic pates.'' But he said companies continue to seek the old standbys: good grades and extra-curricular activities.
</TEXT>
