<BYLINE>By TERRY MUTCHLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Thursday fined <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> $ 50,000 for improperly cutting off electricity to customers, including a family who resorted to using candles that started a fatal fire. The <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION> said the utility also must contribute $ 400,000 to an energy assistance fund for needy families as part of a settlement regarding customer service violations over a two-year period. The most publicized case was last April, when <ORGANIZATION> PECO </ORGANIZATION> cut off electricity to a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> family who used candles to light their home. Eleven days later, a fire started in their row home in the city's <LOCATION> Fairmount </LOCATION> section and killed seven-year-old <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON>. His five-year-old brother <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON> received third-degree burns over 35 percent of his body. An <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION> investigation determined <ORGANIZATION> PECO </ORGANIZATION> did not alert a `` responsible adult'' in the family that service would be terminated but instead told a neighbor. The commission said the utility also did not provide a 48-hour termination notice and would not agree to payment plan offered twice by the family to clear up the delinquent bill. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION>'s consumer research, said the <ORGANIZATION> Blackwells </ORGANIZATION> owed $ 738.01. <ORGANIZATION> PECO </ORGANIZATION> terminated service and wanted $ 338 to reconnect the electricity and asked the family to pay $ 20 a month afterwards. The <ORGANIZATION> Blackwells </ORGANIZATION> received state assistance and could not afford the amount, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> PECO </ORGANIZATION> would not accept any other payment arrangements. `` They treated this family like they were <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>,'' Commissioner <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said. `` They did n't take into consideration, as required by law, -LRB- the <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON>'s -RRB- ability to pay.'' After reading the <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION>'s report, <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> said he concluded `` <ORGANIZATION> PECO </ORGANIZATION>'s violations of regulations directly and significantly contributed to the death of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON> and the maiming of <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON>.'' <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> said he believes the utility's violations and sloppy administration contributed to the fatal fire He said <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> had been fined $ 50,000 for similar violations in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> PECO </ORGANIZATION> was also forced to pay $ 150,000 to an energy assistance fund. <ORGANIZATION> PECO </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> McDermott </PERSON> said the fatal fire can not be linked to the company's termination of service. <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> said it is `` quite disturbing'' that <ORGANIZATION> PECO </ORGANIZATION> did not modify its behavior after the 1987 fines. `` I think a $ 400,000 fine has good possibilities for behavior modification,'' <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> said, noting that the greatest driving force for change `` is the death.'' `` Without question, if you look at the report of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in this case, the company has made substantial p