<HEAD>Rural America Has Low-Income Housing Crisis, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly three of every four rural households pay more for housing than the government considers affordable, with about a quarter of all rural residents living in substandard dwellings, says a new report. `` To many Americans, the low-income housing crisis is primarily an urban problem, calling up visions of homeless men and women sleeping on steam grates and of families in city welfare hotels,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON>, director of the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities. `` Yet in rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, too, there is a crisis in housing for low-income people,'' <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> said. His organization and the <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> coauthored the report released Thursday. Sen. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.C. </LOCATION>, said the report demonstrates the need for his rural housing legislation. <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> has introduced a bill that would increase funding for <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> rural housing programs by $ 500 million over two years, targeting rural communities that traditionally do not get much help from the federal government. `` In my home state of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, 12 rural counties have poverty rates over 20 percent and occupied substandard housing rates over 10 percent,'' said <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON>. `` Some 100,000 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> households still use outhouses.'' The report found that 42 percent of rural poor households spent at least half of their income on housing in 1985, the most recent year for which data is available. It said 26 percent spent 70 percent or more for housing. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> has standards that say housing is not considered affordable unless it is 30 percent or less of a family's income. While an earlier <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> study showed it's more expensive to live in urban areas, the study released by the two organizations Thursday says more rural residents live in substandard housing than city dwellers According to the report, the worst rural housing is in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>. The study showed that 83 percent of all rural housing units with rats were in the South, as were 79 percent of the homes with inadequate waste disposal, 73 percent with holes in the floor, 61 percent with inadequate heating, 53 percent with cracks in the walls and 52 percent with inadequate water supplies. The study was based on data released in February 1989 by the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> in a study called the American Housing Survey of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1985. The Center for Budget and Policy Priorities is an independent research organization that specializes in issues affecting low - and moderate-income groups The Housing Assistance Council promotes development of low-income rural housing through seed-money loans, technical assistance, research and information.
