<HEAD>Pentagon to Halt Round-the-Clock Flights of Airborne Command Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Pentagon has proposed halting round-the-clock flights of an airborne command post that since 1961 has had orders to take charge of nuclear forces if the president and other leaders were killed, The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. According to <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is instead proposing that the planes be changed to `` continuous ground alert with specified number of sorties per week.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> recommendation, made amid growing defense budgetary restraints and the belief the threat of a surprise <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear attack is diminishing, needs President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s authorization. One official told the Times the plan has not drawn strong objections from within the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, where some preliminary defense budget recommendations were reversed after debate. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> maintains on a rotating basis a fleet of planes collectively known as `` Looking Glass'' that has been under the command of the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, Neb. In the event <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> leaders were killed during nuclear war, a SAC general would assume command of nuclear forces. The proposal, which originated at <ORGANIZATION> SAC </ORGANIZATION>, would save about $ 20 million in fiscal 1990. The plan is one of several recommendations to change defense planning and spending.
