<HEAD>Sakharov, the Conscience of Mankind</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 9 `Born in' to INSERT birthdate; SUBS graf 16 `The
Soviets' with two grafs to UPDATE with details of his banishment to Gorky.
Picks up 17th pvs, `In an ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Obit-Sakharov</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From national hero to shunned exile to popular lawmaker, <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s remarkable journey of conscience made him perhaps the world's most celebrated dissident. His life was a great irony: the physicist who developed the Soviet hydrogen bomb went on to become his nation's greatest advocate of human rights at a time when the world lived under the shadow of nuclear war. He spoke out for democracy when many others were silent. He kept speaking out when it became fashionable under the reforms of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Hours before he died at age 68, he stood on the floor of the Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> and demanded that the squabbling opposition form an alternative party to the ruling Communists. `` We can not take on ourselves responsibility for what the leadership is doing now,'' he said, speaking in an official forum the type of words that sent him into internal exile for six years, that won him a Nobel Peace Prize. Selfless, brave and determined, the stooped, disheveled dean of Soviet dissent lived to see many of his dreams come true. His own people began to acknowledge his greatness, as the rest of the world had done earlier. But <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was never satisfied, saluting reforms but faulting their inadequacy. He constantly challenged even the man who turned many of his dreams into reality and set him free after nearly seven years in exile. `` I personally respect <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergeyevich </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> very much, but it is dangerous to give so much power even to the initiator of perestroika,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> boldly told the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in June after it added the presidency to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s job as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> general secretary. Born the son of a physicist on May 21, 1921, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s early fame was not as a political activist but as a brilliant scientist. He was inducted into the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> in 1953 at age 32, the hallowed hall's youngest member ever. In 1948, he joined physicist <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Tamm </PERSON> in developing the hydrogen bomb and for the next 20 years lived and worked in secrecy, with privileges that included a good apartment, a driver, a high salary and a government awards. But, like <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> began to worry about the morality of developing weapons of mass destruction. He had his first major brush with top Soviet officials in 1961, when he appealed to Premier <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> to stop nuclear weapons tests. <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> responded that scientists should n't meddle in politics. Two years later, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed to such limits in a treaty with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, horrified at Soviet society's mistreatment of its own citizens, once said his `` social and political views underwent a major evolution.'' He risked his prestigious position and began using his influence for victims of human rights abuses in 1966, speaking out for those who suffered under dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s repressions The authorities showed their rage in 1968, when <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s `` Progress, Coexistence and Intellectual Freedom'' was published abroad It called for Soviet-American detente well before the concept became part of Soviet foreign policy, saying progress in disarmament is impossible without human rights and political changes in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He was banned from work on secret projects. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> called the essay `` a turning point in my life'' and two years later, he helped found the <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. In 1971, after the death of his first wife, he married <PERSON> Yelena </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> doctor and human rights activist who was to become his constant, feisty companion. In 1975, he won even greater world recognition and was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize. The Soviets, on the other hand, condemned his strong criticism of the 1979 Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. First they stripped him of his awards and then on Jan. 22, 1980, he was pickup up on a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> street and banished to internal exile in <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION>, a closed city 200 miles east. In an autobiographical statement written in 1981, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> reflected on his approach to human rights. `` Moral criteria, in combination with unrestricted inquiry, provide the only possible compass for these complex and contradictory problems. ... Today, as always, I believe in the power of reason and the human spirit,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> wrote. Western governments, scientific and human rights groups pressed the Soviets to release him. In December 1986, a phone was suddenly installed in <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s Gorky apartment, and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> called to say he could return to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, suppressing his joy at the news to show his concern for others, told <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to free all political prisoners. Two months after <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s release, scores of political prisoners were freed and he threw his support behind <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. He gradually was rehabilitated, getting his old job back at the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, speaking at official conferences and giving interviews to the Soviet press. In November 1988, he was allowed to travel abroad for the first time, even though <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> himself had said earlier <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> could not travel to other countries because he had access to state secrets. Although he professed not to aspire to politics, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was elected to represent the Academy in the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Academy leaders had initially rejected him, but had to reverse the decision after a popular outcry. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s rumpled figure and high-pitched voice became familiar to millions of Soviets watching his televised appearances at the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and fellow parliamentarian <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> called him `` the nation's conscience.'' Age and poor health curtailed his human rights activities _ he looked far older than his years _ but when he felt he had to speak out, he did, such as his condemnation of the crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in June 1989 and constant complaints that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic and political reforms did not go far enough. Even though he was a poor speaker _ with a slight stutter and high-pitched voice _ the public had come to know and like <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> so much that an unscientific poll by a Soviet newspaper in October 1989 indicated he was the most popular parliamentarian, outscoring even <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and the maverick Communist <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>. In a February 1989 tribute to <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, the weekly magazine <ORGANIZATION> Ogonyok </ORGANIZATION> `` praised a person who had earlier been cursed'' and published his long-suppressed essays and letters. The Soviet press had come a long way from the pre-glasnost days when it branded him a traitor and `` utterly ignorant person'' who `` groveled before the capitalist order.''
