<HEAD>Durenberger Made 40 Trips to Earn $100,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, R-Minn., made at least 40 expense-paid speaking appearances to earn $ 100,000 through a book contract he's accused of using to launder honoraria, records show His <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> publisher said Thursday the speaking fees enabled him to show a profit on <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>'s two books on health and defense policy and allowed the senator to record the earnings as salary. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which has hired a special counsel to determine whether <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> used the book deal to circumvent <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> honoraria limits, has subpoenaed records from organizations that paid the fees as well as from publisher <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON>. <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> amended his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> financial disclosure statements in recent months to list the 40 expense-paid speaking appearances, many of them in such locales as <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The speaking appearances include an engagement with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Podiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in 1986 where `` there was not even a mention of the book or books,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>, director of government affairs for the group. <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said a $ 2,000 check was sent to <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Piranha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, but he considered it `` from day one up to the current moment as a fee for the purpose of the senator making a speech to our audience.'' <P