<HEAD>FDA Examining Possible Problems on Generic Drug for Leukemia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is investigating reports that high doses of a generic drug used to treat leukemia patients may cause dangerous neurological side effects. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said it is considering how to alert physicians to reports from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> that high doses of generic cytarabine, made by <ORGANIZATION> Quad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, may have more serious neurological side effects than are caused by low doses of the drug. The reports were presented to the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Oncologic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drugs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday at an emergency meeting called by the agency `` because of the serious nature of the problem.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinsler </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> pharmacologist, estimated as many as 3,000 leukemia patients may be candidates for high-dose cytarabine therapy _ about 30 times the normal dose. An official said the concerns were not prompted by <PERSON> Quad </PERSON>'s legal problems with the agency's generic drug division. Earlier this year, the company and a former executive pleaded guilty to charges of bribing <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> chemists to win approval of generic drug applications. Cytarabine is known to have neurological side effects, including loss of muscular coordination and slurred speech. But in high doses it appears these side effects may be more prevalent and more severe, said Dr. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, acting director of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s oncology division `` Nothing is very definitive,'' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. `` It's like a flag signal.'' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said the action the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> takes to alert physicians to the reports will depend on whether Quad decides to take similar action on its own, although he said some action will be taken within the week. Quad officials did not return a telephone call for comment late in the day Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> investigation could not determine whether any patients had died as a result of the effects of the Quad drug. Most of the patients being treated at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>'s medical center were on a combination of drugs, were in advanced stages of the disease and could have had other side effects of the cytarabine, which also suppresses bone marrow and damages the liver, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> was alerted to the possible problem by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> last summer. The medical center returned to using <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION>'s brand-name Cytosar after the side effects of the Quad product were noticed. Analyses of samples of the brand name and generic drugs found they both meet <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> standards, and neither drug appears to cause an unusually large number of neurological problems when used in normal doses, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. However, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials are concerned that when used in high doses, impurities in the Quad drug may worsen the side effects. Impurities resulting from the manufacturing process are different in the two drugs, he said. At high doses the `` relative amount of impurities could make a difference,'' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. The problem could extend to other drugs when they are used in high doses because all drugs contain a certain amount of impurities, he said. He noted doctors have found success in high anti-cancer drug dosages, and because of that, physicians are increasing dosages above the level for which the drug was approved. In the case of cytarabine, the high doses were about 30 times the regular dose, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation of the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> high-dose patients found eight of 25 patients on the Quad drug experienced neurological side effects, while three of 34 patients on the <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> drug had these effects, <PERSON> Rinsler </PERSON> said.
