<HEAD>Disputed Murder Sentence the Product of Racial Tension, Attorney
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The imprisonment of a former black civil rights activist resulted from racial polarization in the state, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>'s lawyer said after a racially split vote by a pardon board to reduce his sentence. The board voted 3-2 Thursday to recommend that Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> reduce the life sentence for <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, who at 16 was condemned to die for the 1974 slaying of a white student during a racial confrontation. The death sentence was automatically changed to life when the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> overturned <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s old death penalty law in 1976. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>'s conviction has withstood all appeals, but the vote would make him eligible for parole in five years. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> will make a decision within a few weeks, his aides said. Parole eligibility is n't the same as freedom for <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, 31, whose entire adult life has been spent in the state prison at <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, said attorney <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>. `` If <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> was white we would n't be here today,'' she told reporters after the pardon board meeting. `` We still do n't see the kind of justice we want in this state.'' The vote _ three black members for reduction in sentence and two whites against _ is representative of `` racial polarization,'' said <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>. `` It's pretty amazing,'' she said. `` In 1985 in Ascension Parish a white kid shot to death an unarmed black kid at a school and was indicted for manslaughter. He was placed on probation and told to finish his education and pay the funeral costs of the victim. `` And, then we have <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, a black kid who police said had a ` smart mouth.''' <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and other human rights organizations have urged freedom for <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, as have more than 12,000 people who signed petitions to the pardon board. The British reggae band UB40 recorded a song about <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> and he was described by the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda in 1978 as a political prisoner. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Juanita </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, said she was happy with the decision, but believes board members would have voted for an immediate release had they interviewed him. Board members routinely do not interview inmates unless they are facing death. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> was active in a school desegregation battle in October 1974 that drew the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> and state police to <LOCATION> Destrehan </LOCATION>, a small town on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> 25 miles north of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. One day, whites surrounded buses of black students at <ORGANIZATION> Destrehan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, shouting and hurling bottles, cans and rocks. A shot was fired from one of the buses. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>, a white student standing with his mother across the schoolyard, fell dead. Witnesses said the pistol was held by a gloved hand. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> was the only one on the bus wearing gloves, said police. Those who believe <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> was framed say that a student who testified against him was known as a liar and that police planted a pistol found in the stuffing of the torn seat where <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> had sat.
