pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opposition leader <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> told his jubilant supporters today that Chileans have regained their freedom by electing him president, ending the dark era of military rule under Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. Chileans danced, waved national flags and set off fireworks to celebrate <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>'s landslide victory Thursday over <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchi </PERSON>, a pro-government candidate. Celebrations lasted into the morning in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> and cities nationwide. The election was intended to bring back democracy to the last <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> country still ruled by the military. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> was forced to call the election after losing a referendum in October last year, in which voters rejected a military proposal that he remain as president until 1997. Speaking to hundreds of supporters early today from the third-floor balcony of a downtown hotel, <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> referred to the generations of democracy enjoyed by Chileans until <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> overthrew elected President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> in a bloody 1973 coup. `` <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> has refound her history. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> has regained liberty. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> has regained democracy,'' said <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, who promised a government of national unity to repair the political and social divisions under the <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> regime. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s government officially recognized <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>'s triumph. Interior Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Caceres </PERSON> said in a nationally broadcast address that authorities would abide by it. Official results from 93 percent of all polling stations in Thursday's election gave <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> 3,577,669 votes or 55.2 percent of all valid ballots. He was supported by a coalition of 17 parties ranging from right to left. <PERSON> Buchi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s former finance minister and architect of a free market economy, had 1,901,668 votes or 29.4 percent. A third candidate, populist businessman <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Errazuriz </PERSON>, had 998,786 votes, 15 percent. <PERSON> Buchi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Errazuriz </PERSON> visited <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> to congratulate him on his victory. His absolute majority and 2-1 advantage over his nearest pro-government challenger appeared to give him the mandate for a possible upper hand in future relations with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who has vowed to remain on as army commander. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, 71, a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> and former <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> president, is to begin a four-year term on March 11, when <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s term ends. Much of his future authority was expected to depend, however, on results from Thursday's voting for the 38 elected <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats and 120 House of Deputies seats. Up to 10 more senators are to be designated by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and other government bodies. Conclusive returns in the congressional races were not expected until later today. However, there were indications from preliminary, unofficial returns that the pro-government forces may have fared better in the congressional vote than in the presidential race. From the moment <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>'s victory became evident, supporters took to the streets, dancing and chanting or roaming in noisy caravans of buses, trucks and automobiles. They waved Chilean flags and party banners, blowing on horns and shooting off fireworks. Similar celebrations were reported in other large cities, and in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> resort city of <PERSON> Vina </PERSON> del Mar, national police used water cannons to clear the streets. Demonstrations are legally banned on election day. Police in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, who had blocked many anti-Pinochet protests and fired water cannons and tear gas at demonstrators in the past, did not intefere with the celebrations and even suspended traffic on the city's main boulevard to allow <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> supporters to listen to their leader's victory speech. `` It's forbidden,'' said a police lieutenant at the scene, `` but there's no problem.'' Ending his speech, <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> urged the demonstrators to return peacefully and to attend a celebration rally tonight. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, in a bref conversation with reporters, said he was not disturbed by <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>'s victory. `` They were better organized. They know how to do things,'' he said. The election was peaceful, with voters arriving early at the polls and waiting patiently in long lines, sometimes for hours, to cast their ballots. Nearly all 7.5 million elegible voters cast their votes. <PERSON> Caceres </PERSON> said Chileans should take pride on the peaceful manner the election took place and for the high turnout, and praised the armed forces for maintaining order. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> lauded the `` maturity'' of the population, and also said the armed forces deserved praise for carrying out a clean election. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> becomes the eighth South American nation in a decade to return to civilian rule. Others include <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. In February, Paraguayan <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> ended more than three decades of rule by Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, overthrowing him and declaring a presidential election, which <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> won.
