<HEAD>Chile Eighth South American Nation in a Decade to Return to Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chileans elected a new president, in a process that brought civilian government back to the last country in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> still ruled by the military. With the election Thursday, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> becomes the eighth nation to undergo such a transition in the last decade. The others are:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> _ 1979. President <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Roldos </PERSON> <PERSON> Aguilera </PERSON> takes office, ending a decade of military dictatorship. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> _ 1980. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Belaunde </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> wins election and reassumes the presidency, ending a 12-year period of military rule that began with his overthrow in a coup 12 years before. <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> _ 1982. The election of veteran former president <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Siles </PERSON> <PERSON> Suazo </PERSON> puts an end to a series of military governments, including one that blocked him from taking office after an election two years earlier. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> _ 1983. After seven years under four successive military juntas, the nation elects civilian President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> _ 1985. <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON>, elected in late 1984, takes office to restore civilian rule in one of south <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most traditional democracies The armed forces had seized power 11 years earlier. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> _ 1985. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> becomes president, replacing <PERSON> Tancredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Neves </PERSON>, who died hours before he was to take office, having been picked by an electoral college. More than two decades of military control came to an end. <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> _ 1989. After more than three decades of authoritarian rule by Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, another general, <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> toppled him in a coup. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> then wins election as the new president.
