<HEAD>Sakharov Fought Until the End to Reform Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Sakharov, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An increasingly radical and disillusioned <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> fought until the end to keep the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on the path of reform started by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. He died late Thursday while writing a speech to the Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> demanding the Communists' constitutional guarantee to power be revoked, his family said. His last words to them were: `` Tomorrow there will be a battle.'' Hours earlier, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> made an uncompromising, if not eloquent, appeal to create a formal political opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and to build a multiparty democracy. `` We can not take on ourselves responsibility for what the leadership is doing now,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Inter-Regional </ORGANIZATION> group. `` It is leading the country to catastrophe, prolonging the process of perestroika many years.'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s high-pitched voice, rambling style and stammer made him a poor public speaker, and despite the group's respect for him, the hum of other conversations in the hall increased as <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> spoke. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> spent his last several days working in the seat of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> power where, until just a few short years ago, he was roundly and regularly condemned. Having supported <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms in 1987 after the Soviet leader brought him back from internal exile, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> had taken an increasingly critical view recently that brought him into conflict with his president. He and other radicals had called for a two-hour general strike Monday to press for elimination of Article 6 of the Soviet Constitution, which makes the Communist Party the `` leading and guiding force of Soviet society and the nucleus of its political system.'' His last exchange with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, shown on live television several hours after the opening of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' winter session on Tuesday, was a bitter one. Having cut off another deputy who wished to take the podium, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> invited <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> to address the 2,250-member <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> urged the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to strike `` all the articles hindering the passing of laws on land, property and other bills promoting perestroika.'' When he began to speak about the party's monopoly on power, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> halted him with a curt `` thank you.'' `` I am under the impression that neither you nor we will know how to realize your suggestion,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` Who is to define what articles to exclude?'' When <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> turned to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and handed him a stack of telegrams in support of his position, the Soviet leader retorted: `` You come to me, I will give you three files of telegrams.'' Undaunted, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> continued to press the issue. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was elected one of five leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Inter-Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> when it was formed in August, and he recently had become one of its more radical and outspoken members. Dressed in a brown suit, he sat at the end of the head table, his chair pushed back and forehead in hand, at the group's meeting Thursday. With him at the table were the group's other leaders: historian <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Afanasyev </PERSON>, Communist maverick <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> and economists <PERSON> Gavriil </PERSON> <PERSON> Popov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Palm </PERSON>. The general strike he pressed for on Monday failed, and that tactic was widely criticized by <ORGANIZATION> Inter-Regional </ORGANIZATION> deputies Thursday. One deputy said the strike call was `` present No. 1'' to the conservatives controlling the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and that the formation of a political opposition would be `` present No. 2.'' Historian <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, a long-time acquaintance who also serves in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview that Thursday had been a `` difficult day'' for <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>. `` He was n't a politician, and did n't always realize the consequences of his actions, but he never gave in to circumstances,'' <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said.
