<FIRST>r a PM-Tranquilizers-HipFractures     12-15 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tranquilizers-Hip Fractures,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Hip Fractures Judged Preventable With Switch in Tranquilizers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-CDC--Smoking Survey, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of elderly people fall and fracture their hips because they take long-lasting sleeping pills, mainly Valium, <LOCATION> Librium </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Dalmane </PERSON>, instead of shorter-acting drugs, a researcher says. The long-acting drugs are no more effective than related, shorter-acting drugs, but the long-acting drugs were developed first, and some doctors still are prescribing them to the elderly, said epidemiologist <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> is co-author of a study published in today's edition of the Journal of the American Medical Association that found people over 65 who took the long-lasting benzodiazepine drugs were 70 percent more likely to sustain hip fractures than those who took no such drugs. But shorter-acting benzodiazepines carried no higher risk, the study said. `` Hip fracture is a serious injury,'' <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> said. He noted that about 250,000 elderly people fall and break their hips annually in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, resulting in monetary costs of $ 6 billion. The human costs are even higher, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> said: a 20 percent increased death rate in the year after the fracture; a loss of ability to walk unassisted among up to half the victims; and entry into nursing homes among up to a third of victims. Hip fractures mark `` the beginning of the end'' for many elderly people, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, an associate professor of preventive medicine at <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview Thursday. He estimated that 10 percent to 15 percent of people over 65 take benzodiazepine drugs, the most commonly prescribed tranquilizers and sleeping pills because of their effectiveness and relative safety. `` All have the side effects of reducing coordination and alertness,'' <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> said, but long-acting benzodiazepines require days to be eliminated while shorter-acting ones are largely eliminated in hours. He estimated thousands of hip fractures could be prevented each year if older people stopped using the long-acting drugs. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>'s team studied all the hip fractures reported among people 65 and older between 1977 and 1985 in <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, an area chosen because its health-care system has unusually complete records. The researchers compared use of benzodiazepine tranquilizers and sleeping pills among 4,501 victims of hip fracture and a control group of 24,041 Canadians matched for comparison. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> said patients should be encouraged to seek non-drug alternatives that will help them relax or sleep, such as reducing caffeine intake, getting more exercise and going to bed later. Three drugs accounted for 95 percent of the long-acting medications taken by study subjects: diazepam, marketed as Valium; flurazepam, marketed as Dalmane; and chlordiazepoxide, marketed as <LOCATION> Librium </LOCATION>. All are manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Nutley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattison </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>, said Thursday, `` It's been generally recognized that there are some adverse effects like this on the elderly. But side effects of the short-acting drugs are less well-known and less predictable than those of longer-acting ones, she said. `` Research needs to be completed to identify geriatric patients that may be at highest risk of hip fracture at the same time as taking benzodiazepines,'' Ms. <PERSON> Mattison </PERSON> said. Short-acting benzodiazepines that accounted for 95 percent of those taken by subjects in the study were: triazolam, marketed as Halcion by the <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; oxazepam, marketed as Serax by <ORGANIZATION> Wyeth-Ayerst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Phildelphia </LOCATION>; and lorazepam, marketed as Ativan by <ORGANIZATION> Wyeth-Ayerst </ORGANIZATION>.
