<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former prostitute who accused the priest who founded a runaway shelter of financial and sexual improprieties is welcome to come back in off the streets, the Rev. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> said after denying the charges. `` If he came back today we would welcome him back to <ORGANIZATION> Convenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> said at a news conference Thursday. `` There are many people here who care very deeply about him.'' Prosecutor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgenthau </PERSON> confirmed Wednesday he was investigating the man's charges of financial improprieties by <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON>. The 20-year-old former <ORGANIZATION> Covenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> resident also reportedly claimed he had a sexual relationship with the Franciscan priest. `` I categorically deny these allegations,'' <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> said. `` They are simply nonsense.'' <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> and the authorities have not publicly identified the man, but a law enforcement source identified him as <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> said the charges were `` deeply offensive to me,'' and had seriously harmed the image of the charitable organization. An audit, he said, `` found our books in perfect order. Every penny is accounted for.'' <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> founded <ORGANIZATION> Covenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> for homeless teen-agers in 1969 and has built it into an $ 85 million-a-year operation with seven shelters in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, one in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> and four in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. More than 90 percent of its funding is private. Covenant House directly serves about 25,000 children annually, and its national telephone line gets about a million calls for help a year. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> said the young man came to the agency early this year saying he was a runaway prostitute being pursued by organized crime. Covenant House in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> currently has about 150 other runaways in similar straits, he said. They are given special attention and a personal mentor. `` I chose to become his mentor because, frankly, I had more experience than anyone else,'' he said. Staff members took the man to their homes on special occasions, and <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> acknowledged traveling with him on a few occasions, but said there were no sexual relations. The man was enrolled at <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, but eventually dropped out and lapsed back into prostitution. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> blamed himself for not spending enough time with the young man. `` We tried so very hard, and we failed,'' he said. `` It is probably better to say that I failed. ... I thought I knew more than I did.'' Asked why the man would have accused him of such transgressions, <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> replied, `` I honestly, simply do not know.'' He said he last spoke with the man in early November, telling him to either go back to college or get a job. The man refused either option and left the apartment <ORGANIZATION> Covenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had provided him on Dec. 5, he said. The priest said he was most concerned that supporters `` have had their faith in me shattered,'' and would not be willing to continue their aid. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON>, who has pursued a vigorous travel schedule in recent years despite a bout with cancer, calls <ORGANIZATION> Covenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> `` an intensive care unit for dying children.'' `` We help about one-third of the kids that come in,'' he said in an interview last year. `` We lose the rest.''
