<HEAD>Toyota Seeks to Set Aside Multimillion Dollar Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sales </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> will ask a judge to set aside a $ 43.2 million judgment for a woman whose husband and two daughters burned to death in a 1982 car fire, officials said. Jurors in a state district court awarded $ 18.2 million in actual damages and $ 25 million in exemplary damages _ the largest ever against <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> _ to <PERSON> Nike </PERSON> <PERSON> Adegbite </PERSON>, 36, who watched as her family and two others were killed in the fire. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON>, vice president and general counsel for <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Torrance </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said the company was surprised and disappointed by Wednesday's verdict, and will ask for a new trial. If the judge refuses, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> will appeal the judgment, <PERSON> West </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Adegbite </PERSON> escaped with only minor burns and cuts from the 1973 <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corona </ORGANIZATION> station wagon when it caught fire after being rear-ended by a van. Her husband, <PERSON> Adeyemi </PERSON>, 35, and her daughters, <PERSON> Yetunde </PERSON>, 7, and <PERSON> Adeloa </PERSON>, 8 months, were killed. The van's driver, <PERSON> Boyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Adetoye </PERSON>, received minor injuries, but his wife and child were killed. Mrs. <PERSON> Adegbite </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfeiffer </PERSON>, said the lawsuit claimed <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> was negligent in its design of the station wagon and failed to recall it. The trial lasted six weeks. The attorney said Mrs. <PERSON> Adegbite </PERSON> and her family were in the back seat of the station wagon when it was struck on a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> highway Sept. 26, 1982. The van's impact pushed the station wagon's gasoline tank forward, <PERSON> Pfeiffer </PERSON> said, and the tank was punctured by an empty spare tire carrier and a valve on the rear axle <PERSON> Adetoye </PERSON> was not involved in the case because he had reached a settlement on a similar lawsuit about a year ago, <PERSON> Pfeiffer </PERSON> said. The settlement amount was not disclosed. <PERSON> West </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> has never had any other claims against the design of the vehicle. He added the company denies any defects or negligence in the vehicle's design. Lawyers on both sides expressed surprise at the size of the judgment. `` We were of course surprised at the verdict _ not only by the extraordinary amount, but that the jury decided against us,'' <PERSON> West </PERSON> said. Previously, the largest award against <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> was about $ 5 million, he said. Ms. <PERSON> Adegbite </PERSON> was surprised, too, said <PERSON> Pfeiffer </PERSON>. `` I think everybody was. It was an emotional moment,'' he said.
