<HEAD>Fatal Fire Prompts New Call for Study of Va. Elderly Housing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire that killed four retirement home residents _ the fifth blaze in six months at a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> nursing or retirement home _ renewed a call for a study of fire safety in the state's housing for the elderly. The fire Thursday at <ORGANIZATION> Shenandoah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retirement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> was the third fatal fire there in 13 years. It injured 23 people, but residents, rescue workers and TV cameramen ushered others to safety in early-morning cold. A preliminary report on the cause of the fire probably would be released today, said Capt. Mark Light of the <LOCATION> Roanoke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> fire and rescue department. After an Oct. 5 fire killed 12 residents of a nursing home in <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, state Sen. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, D-Norfolk, drafted the bill calling for the fire-safety study. Lawmakers will consider it next year. `` It's sad that it takes a tragedy to get people to move,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said Thursday. The fire broke out shortly after 2 a.m. in a third-floor apartment at <ORGANIZATION> Shenandoah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION>. Only the second floor of the six-story building is licensed as a home for adults and regulated by the state. The remaining floors are considered a boarding home because residents require less medical care than in adult homes and nursing homes, state officials said. Residents, many wearing only pajamas, streamed out of exits into the 19-degree cold. Some were aided by wheelchairs and walkers and others were helped by fellow residents, rescue personnel and even TV cameramen. `` I left my walker, got my cane and everybody helped each other get out,'' said <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Branson </PERSON>, 78, wrapped in a blanket. `` It was just a marvel how these elderly people reacted under pressure,''