<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The two candidates vying to become <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s first popularly elected president in nearly three decades traded barbs and insults in a crucial nationwide debate. The 2 -LCB- - hour showdown between <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>, a center-right former governor, and leftist <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Inacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Lula </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> comes in the stretch drive of Sunday's election New polls show that <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> has erased a 15-point deficit in the last two weeks to make the race almost dead even. Both candidates ducked questions about inflation, expected to rise 50 percent in December alone. Instead they traded personal barbs during the debate that began Thursday and ended early today. <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>, shouting and shaking his fists in the air at times, called his socialist rival `` intolerant'' and `` backward'' and said the election of <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> would prompt nationwide strikes and economic chaos. <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> labeled <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> as `` emotionally unstable'' and a member of the `` archaic upper class.'' <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, 44, a congressman of the <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and former labor leader, instead focused on issues such as redistribution of land and wealth and state-funded health care and educational reforms. <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> said if elected he would suspend payments on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s $ 110 billion foreign debt, the Third World's largest, and invest the money for social programs <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> paid $ 14 billion last year servicing its foreign debt, acc