<FIRST>r a PM-Judge-Sentencing     12-15 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge-Sentencing,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disclosure Shows Judges' Resentment of New Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new federal drug law that imposes mandatory prison sentences is drawing complaints from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> judges who say their authority is being undermined. `` I do n't think it's the world's most popular thing with judges,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON>, chief federal judge for the Northern District of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` We get in this business and over the years presumably develop some educated discretion with respect to disposition of criminal cases, and that just takes discretion away. You have to comply with the statute, but I think many judges wish the statute would be repealed.'' Two weeks ago, the issue came to a boil in the courtroom of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnacke </PERSON>, a former longtime federal prosecutor and 1970 judicial appointee of President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. The case was one where a crack cocaine prosecution in state court, with a maximum 12-year sentence, was transferred by prosecutors to federal court where penalties are stiffer _ in this case, a mandatory life term without parole because of defendant <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>'s two prior convictions. As jurors prepared to deliberate, <PERSON> Schnacke </PERSON> said he would normally tell them to ignore possible penalties because those were up to him. But since he had no choice of sentence, he said, they should know that a conviction would be punished by life without parole. On Dec. 1, the jury acquitted <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, 30, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, of the drug charge, convicting him only of a gun-possession charge that has yet to be sentenced. <PERSON> Schnacke </PERSON> thanked the jurors `` for what I take to be an expression of concern about the nature of the compelled sentencing process that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has imposed upon the courts.'' The new federal drug law, effective last November, requires prison sentences without parole for certain types of drug crimes _ decisions that were formerly left up to the sentencing judge. A first offender who possessed over 50 grams of crack cocaine for sale, for example, must serve at least 10 years without parole. With a prior felony drug conviction, the minimum sentence is 20 years, and with two prior drug felonies the mandatory sentence is life without the possibility of parole. `` Mandatory minimum -LRB- sentences -RRB- applied to some kinds of cases result in shocking injustice,'' said federal Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzer </PERSON>. `` Judges are going to struggle to find ways to perform their sworn constitutional duty to do justice.'' Federal judges at all levels in the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, which covers <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and eight other Western states, voted overwhelmingly earlier this year to urge <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to repeal the mandatory sentencing laws. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Russoniello </PERSON> said <PERSON> Schnacke </PERSON>'s action was unprecedented and had virtually dictated the verdict, although <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>'s lawyer quoted jurors as saying the prosecution had failed to prove drug possession. <PERSON> Russoniello </PERSON> complained to <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Solicitor General <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON>, but conceded there was nothing he could do because an acquittal can not be appealed.
