<HEAD>Nurse Faces 50 Years to Life for Deaths of Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jurors wept as they heard the testimony of a patient who survived a dose of a paralyzing drug from a hospital nurse, then convicted <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> for causing four deaths. <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> stared straight ahead Thursday during the reading of the verdict finding him guilty of murder in two deaths, manslaughter in a third and criminally negligent homicide in a fourth. `` What this guy did to all of these people is beyond words,'' said a sobbing <PERSON> Kieran </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, 24, whose father, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, was one of <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON>'s victims. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> hugged prosecutor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> after the verdict was announced. <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON>, 27, faces a maximum of 50 years to life for the murders when sentenced Jan. 17. Less than an hour before the verdict, jurors in the eighth day of deliberations listened to testimony by former patient <PERSON> Gerolamo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kucich </PERSON>, a 75-year-old Yugoslavian. `` I was actually putting myself in his shoes,'' juror <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Loguercio </PERSON> said of <LOCATION> Kucich </LOCATION>. `` I walked out of there in tears this morning.'' <PERSON> Kucich </PERSON> testified during the trial that while he was a patient <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> had given him an injection saying it would `` make me feel better.'' Instead, <PERSON> Kucich </PERSON> was left fighting for breath. `` This is probably a fair verdict,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Naiburg </PERSON>. The injections, lethal doses of muscle relaxants, occurred at <ORGANIZATION> Good </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Samaritan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islip </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in the fall of 1987. <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON>, who was a nurse in the intensive care unit for about six months, admitted to police he had planned to inject the patients, then be first on the scene to revive them and be seen as a hero. The jury also convicted <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> on Thursday of assault charges in the deaths and in the injections he gave <PERSON> Kucich </PERSON>. He was acquitted of assaulting two patients whose deaths were not proved to be from the drugs. <PERSON> Naiburg </PERSON> had conceded in his closing statement that <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> injected the patients and that he may have caused some of their deaths. But he had argued that <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> was not aware that the injections presented a grave risk to the patients, a condition necessary for a murder conviction. He had urged the jurors to find <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> guilty of criminally negligent homicide, a lesser charge punishable by up to four years in jail. The prosecutor, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, calling <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> `` a monster in nurse's whites,'' had argued that <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> had to know the risks involved, especially after the first victim died. <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials exhumed 33 bodies of patients at Good Samaritan who died suspiciously during <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON>'s tenure. The medical examiner found traces of Pavulon in six of the bodies exhumed. A Pavulon-laced syringe was found in <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON>'s apartment the day before his arrest. County Court Judge <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> remanded <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> without bail Thursday to the county jail, where he has been held since his arrest.
