<SECOND>PM-India-Moslems,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Curfew Imposed in Moslem City, Security Tightened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ASKARI ZAIDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities imposed an curfew here today to prevent Moslem separatists from celebrating the government's decision to free five jailed militants in ransom deal The government released the five to secure the freedom of a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister's daughter held captive by Moslem militants for six days. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, new Prime Minister V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> met with reporters for the first time as chief of state and defended his decision to release the militants. `` We are not bowing to terrorists. We saw the overall situation and took the decision,'' said <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, who assumed power earlier this month, succeeding <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said the government would review the situation in the northern state of <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION>, where militant Moslems are finding increasing support for their campaign to secede from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. `` We will assess the situation but are not in favor of precipitate action because it is a delicate situation,'' he said. `` There are a lot of problems at the people's level. We have to tackle it in a very deft way with a lot of flexibility.'' <PERSON> S.S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, deputy inspector general of police in <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION> state, said security forces had orders to shoot curfew violators. Witnesses said police fired at a group of people who tried to defy curfew in <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION>, home of 700,000 people and the summer capital of <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION> state. But they did not know if there were any casualties. About 150 soldiers were called out in <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION>, and two armored personnel carriers were stationed at the city's main intersection, witnesses said. Paramiliitary troops from the <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> also were deployed in the towns of <LOCATION> Anantnag </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baramulla </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Anantnag </LOCATION>, Moslem militants fired at a police patrol and injured one policeman, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said. Police returned fire, injuring six of the attackers. The jailed militants, all members of the <ORGANIZATION> Kashmir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, were released Wednesday in exchange for <PERSON> Rubaiya </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>, a medical intern and the daughter of Home Minister <PERSON> Mufti </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>, a Moslem and a Kashmiri. Ms. <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>, 22, was kidnapped on Dec. 8, and her release came after five days of hectic negotiations with the abductors who twice threatened to kill her. The swap sparked celebtations in the Moslem-majority state and large groups of people shouted anti-India slogans and waved the national flag of neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The militants have been demanding the secession of the state from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and gaining either autonomy of assimilation into <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` We fear that the terrorists may try to create lots of disturbance, hence we have taken the steps,'' <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s only Moslem majority state. Moslems make up 64 percent of the state's 5 million people, but only about 11 percent of the country's 880 million people. The <ORGANIZATION> Kashmir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, formed in 1965, advocates secession of <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION> to become either independent or part of <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> is claimed by both <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, and the two countries have fought three wars over the territory since gaining independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1947. A ceasefire line mointored by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> separates the state into Indian and Pakistani territory. On Thursday, two teen-age boys were killed when security forces fired on rampaging Moslems separatists in <LOCATION> Sapore </LOCATION> town. Moslems mobs attacked a police station and freed some prisoners. Trouble spread to the neighboring town of <LOCATION> Baramullah </LOCATION>, where violent mobs attacked an army motor convoy, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said. An 18-year-old boy, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Yusuf </PERSON>, was killed when soldiers opened fire on the crowd in self-defense, he said. Curfew was imposed in both towns Thursday. Both towns are about 35 miles north of <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON> is the first Moslem to be named to the sensitive post that oversees police and internal security. The appointment on Dec. 5 was seen as part of the Singh's efforts to appease <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s Moslem minority who have borne the brunt of Hindu-Moslem religious riots this fall that claimed 300 lives.
