<HEAD>State Drops $100 Million Santa Monica Bay Pollution Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state water agency dropped its $ 100 million lawsuit against the city in exchange for municipal promises to spend even more to cut the flow of pollution into once pristine <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. The bay fronting some of the world's most-visited beaches has provided background scenery to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> productions, including the `` Beach Blanket'' movies, `` Gidget'' TV series and the film `` Tequila Sunrise.'' It touches about 40 miles of wide, white-sand beach from the <LOCATION> Palos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verdes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION> in the south to <LOCATION> Malibu </LOCATION> in the north. The agreement between the <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and the city of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> lists 22 measures the city must pursue, with costs estimated to surpass $ 100 million, officials said Thursday. `` This is the way controversies between two government agencies should be handled,'' Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. `` Instead of fighting it out in the courts, we solved it at the bargaining table.'' The city agreed to take steps to prevent raw sewage spills at a treatment plant, reduce pollutants washing out to sea from storm drains and improve sewage treatment. A rash of sewage spills in 1987 prompted county health officials to close miles of beach, angering surfers, scuba divers and environmentalists. The city also pledged to create new water reclamation and conservation programs and stage a museum exhibit to heighten public awareness on bay pollution. The pact was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in a closed-door meeting Tuesday and announced on Thursday. Virtually all costs will be borne by the city's sewage surcharge tax imposed on homeowners and commercial landlords, city officials said. State Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> filed the suit in 1987, seeking penalties of up to $ 20 a gallon for two major spills that dumped more than 5.4 million gallons of raw sewage into the bay.
