<HEAD>AIDS Tests to be Done on NYC Autopsies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Every autopsy at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> medical examiner's office will include an AIDS test in an effort to inform other people if they may be infected with the virus, according to a published report today. The test results will be used in statistical research and in `` contact-tracing,'' the tracking of an AIDS sufferer's sexual partners or drug-needle sharers, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said. Officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> said they were unaware of any other such program in the country. About 8,000 autopsies are performed every year by the medical examiner's office. Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>, the chief medical examiner, said he expected to detect the AIDS virus in about 1,000 of the autopsies. The testing has been approved by Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> and was authorized Monday by the medical examiner's advisory board. The results and the names of people who have been contacted will be kept confidential. <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> said testing would begin by year's end after he discussed the program with groups involved with AIDS issues. Some people have expressed concern that contact-tracing may lead to invasion of privacy. But <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, the city's health commissioner, denied that. `` What argument can anyone make to not warn the unsuspecting partner of someone who is dead?'' he said. `` It's very compelling _ the absolute need to warn people at risk who might not learn any other way.'' He said the program will be useful in evaluating the extent of the virus's spread in the city and be an `` extremely useful tool for epidemiologic control and prevention.'' There are 75,000 deaths every year in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Autopsies are carried out for unusual or unexplained deaths, and are required in homicides, suicides and deaths from drug overdose. Many of those who die for unexplained reasons are believed to carry the AIDS virus, particularly intravenous drug users.
