<HEAD>Robert Morse Plays Truman Capote on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs with other critics' reviews. No pickup. No PMs
planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Underneath all the celebrity, writer <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> <PERSON> Capote </PERSON> was a melancholy, lonely little man. That's one of the points playwright <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Presson </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> makes with surprising poignancy in `` Tru,'' her terrific one-man show based on the life of the well-known literary personality. The play, which opened Thursday night at Broadway's Booth Theater, examines a specific, highly publicized life, but its lessons are universal. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> takes the man and makes his plight moving. Capote, defeated by too much high and low life, becomes the victim of his success. Or rather the success he has ca n't compensate for the rejection he feels from family, friends, lovers and a fickle public In the play, the pudgy, pint-sized Capote prowls his plush apartment at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plaza </ORGANIZATION>. He tattles on the telephone in search of `` a dirt fix,'' talks into a tape recorder for a biographer and eventually ends up speaking directly to the audience about his strange, unhappy life. The show takes place in the week before Christmas 1975. It's a momentous time for Capote, just after <ORGANIZATION> Esquire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> published an excerpt from his novel-in-progress `` Answered Prayers.'' In it, Capote savages some of his rich, female friends, such people as <PERSON> Babe </PERSON> <PERSON> Paley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Keith </PERSON>. Much to his surprise and anger, they cut him off. `` You'd think I killed the <PERSON> Lindbergh </PERSON> baby,'' he whines. Capote proclaims himself an artist, and a true artist has no friends, he says. But the man still craves the acceptance of these people. Their abandonment hurts him just as much as when his own mother left him as a child with her sisters in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. There are some sweet remembrances of that time, including a reading from `` A Christmas Memory,'' a heart-breaking holiday story about his childhood and his favorite aunt. Capote is played with astonishing fidelity by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Morse </PERSON>. The actor, best known as a brash musical comedy performer, is a revelation, and not only because of <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Haney </PERSON>'s remarkable makeup which transforms him into a credible likeness of Capote. His Capote is wickedly funny, a sly imp ready to deliver an off-color joke about the Queen Mum, zing <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Goulet </PERSON> or rhapsodize about the time he tap-danced for <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>. His voice is soft and sibilant, his body language languid, except when he dives into a dance, bopping to `` The Girl From <LOCATION> Ipanema </LOCATION>.'' But there's a desperate side to Capote, too, and <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> rises to the pain. The playwright conjures up a devastating moment in Act 2 when <PERSON> Capote </PERSON> puts his fist through a portrait of himself as a young man, a beautiful golden boy who let his life fall apart. It earns gasps from the audience. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> deftly weaves biographical facts into the evening, refusing to present <PERSON> Capote </PERSON> as merely a case study. The production, which the playwright also directed, rarely falters as it builds to the loneliest of Christmas Eves. The luxurious apartment designed by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> offers an appropriately panoramic view of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and the gaudy furnishings include Capote's own sofa lent by <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>. It's an opulent, colorful setting, the perfect environment for <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s extravagant, colorful subject. But Capote, who died in 1984, probably would have been interesting wherever he was and so is the play. `` Tru'' is an affecting portrait of a gifted but peculiar writer, whose saddest story turned out to be his own. Broadway critics praised <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> in the one-man show. They also applauded <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> but wished that he had delved deeper into Capote's persona <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> called <PERSON> Morse </PERSON>'s performance a tour de force and said that with the <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s help, <PERSON> Capote </PERSON> `` really does live again.'' The Daily News' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> `` captures both -LRB- Capote's -RRB- wit and malice beautifully,'' and that <PERSON> Morse </PERSON>'s work is `` sheer joy.'' `` It is a shock, not to mention a pleasure and delight, to stumble on Capote's ghost in the unlikely person of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Morse </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Winer </PERSON> in today's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Newsday </LOCATION>. But she said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> unfortunately does not touch the mysteries of what made Capote a great writer, when he was up to it. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, wishing for a stronger play, said `` in place of a life portrait with depth, ` Tru' settles for its wind-up Madame Tussauds's caricature of the wrecked 1975 model Capote.'' And while applauding <PERSON> Morse </PERSON>'s efforts, he said his performances leaves one eager to see him in other works.
</TEXT>
