<HEAD>Scottish Officer Orders Inquiry Into Flight 103 Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with plane reconstructed by investigators,
background on other probes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s chief law officer today announced the first public inquiry into the bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103, which exploded over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> and killed 270 people. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, the Lord Advocate, said criminal prosecution was not imminent but that he still hoped to find the terrorists who planted the bomb in a suitcase that brought down the flight on Dec. 21, 1988. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747, packed with Christmas travelers heading to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, exploded over the Scottish town of <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, killing all 259 people on board and 11 on the ground. Investigators displayed pictures at a news conference today showing how they had reconstructed the part of the plane where the explosion occurred, with a gaping hole in the forward cargo section. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> said aircraft often are reconstructed but that this represented `` quite an achievement'' because it involved many small pieces scattered over a large area. Police had said earlier they had recovered 85 percent of the aircraft. In a statement released at the news conference, <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said the fatal accident inquiry _ similar to a coroner's inquest _ will be held next year but that a date and place had not been set. The inquiry's scope will include whether `` reasonable precautions'' might have avoided the tragedy and possible `` defects'' in any system that might have contributed to the deaths, <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said. He said the announcment was made today to give authorities time to organize the inquiry and notify people, and that it had nothing to do with the first anniversary of the crash next week. Fatal accident inquiries are conducted by a sheriff sitting without a jury. The sheriff will issue a finding on the evidence. <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said the inquiry would have power under Scottish law to order foreign evidence, although it could not request people overseas to appear. Relatives of the victims are entitled to attend or be represented. Investigators remain determined `` to bring the evil perpetrators of this mass murder to justice,'' <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said. `` This appalling terrorist outrage ... was an affront ... to civilized people everywhere.'' There are two investigations already under way in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the criminal probe headed by the <LOCATION> Dumfries </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Galloway </PERSON> <PERSON> Constabulary </PERSON> and a crash probe by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION>'s Air Accident Investigation branch. Neither of those investigations are being held in public. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Esson </PERSON>, chief of the constabulary, said his investigation had focused on the Popular Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> PFLP-GC </ORGANIZATION>, an extremist Palestinian group headed by <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jibril </PERSON>. `` It would be right to say that we have focused our attention on one group, but it would be unwise to rule out other possibilities,'' he said. Asked whether that group was the <ORGANIZATION> PFLP-GC </ORGANIZATION>, he said: `` Certainly.'' Investigators have said a bomb made of plastic explosive was packed in a <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> radio-cassette player and hidden in a suitcase, which was loaded into a forward cargo hold. They displayed a photo today showing the reconstructed metal container which held the suitcase bomb. <PERSON> Esson </PERSON> said Scottish investigators still believe the suitcase bomb `` either started or passed through the <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport,'' where the flight originated. West German police maintain there is not enough evidence to prove that. <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> and <PERSON> Esson </PERSON> were asked about <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON>, a member of another radical Palestinian group who is charged in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> with four bombings in northern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He was identified in a Swedish court as a suspect in the <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> bombing and police seized clothing from his home, reportedly to compare with shreds of clothing found in the wreckage. `` I have at present no intention to seek the extradition of <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Esson </PERSON> said: `` He is certainly an individual in whom we have an interest.'' He added that investigators wanted to talk with many people, but he refused to identify them further. <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, asked about the contents of the baggage that contained the bomb, said investigators also had found `` items of clothing which have been further identified and located.'' He refused to elaborate. <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> denied that he was pessimistic about prosecutions and said investigators had made `` impressive'' progress aided by outstanding forensic work and unprecedented international cooperation. `` What we are doing in effect is trying to piece together an international terrorist jigsaw,'' <PERSON> Esson </PERSON> said. `` We have some of the pieces, some we are trying to place, and some we have yet to find.''
