<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Keeping the Ideological Fires Burning</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Deletes superfluous words ``any of'' 13th graf, The Sandinistas.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crumbling of communist rule in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is prompting some to proclaim that history, at least in terms of ideological struggle, is over and the championship belt goes to democratic capitalism. Not so fast, say dissenters on the left. History is not over by a long shot. Do n't count Marxism out just yet. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, longtime <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Communist Party leader <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> yearns for the good old days when the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was less inclined toward revisionist thought. Hall was so incensed at the irreverent views of a leading Soviet reform organ, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> News, that he urged his allies in the birthplace of <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> to have the editor removed. Otherwise, said <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, they could `` burn down the god-damn building. I mean get rid of it.'' As <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> sees it, the interests of class struggle preclude capitalism's right to exist. Hall also had no patience with pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, finding them entirely too pro-American. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s views may seem increasingly quaint in a world where Marxists increasingly are on the defensive, but the far left does not give up easily. In this hemisphere, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> still boasts a devout following among some of his countrymen and the leftist cause continues to persuade many in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> to take up arms. Do n't tell the Salvadoran rebels that democratic capitalists are on the side of history. They see around them all the evils that <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> spoke of: exploitation, class stratification, disease, unemployment and illiteracy. To these combatants, there is considerable allure to a philosophy _ socialism _ which `` guarantees'' equality and the right to health care, education and employment. The Salvadoran militants do n't want to hear about the hundreds of thousands who have been demonstrating in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> for the past two months demanding an end to 40 years of misrule. They want an end to more than a century and a half of misrule in their own country. Obviously there are many in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> who believe that a rebel-led government would only make things worse. And do n't tell the hard-liners within <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leadership about the wonders of democratic capitalism. Most of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has lived under elected civilian governments for the past decade, a period marked by one of the steepest economic declines in the region's history. The Sandinistas blame the armed uprising <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has been supporting for almost a decade for their inability to improve the lot of their citizens. Perhaps the most irrepressible defender of the Marxist faith these days is <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, who believes someone must stand up for the `` thousands of millions of people in the world who live in inhuman conditions.'' <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> blames this state of affairs on the `` colossal looting'' of imperialist countries, led by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Do n't talk to <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> about the more than 200,000 East Germans who have fled to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> this year. He'd rather talk about the 40,000 children who die each day around the world _ a <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> and a <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>, as he puts it, every three days. Standing before a gathering of his countrymen last week, <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> warned of the dangers of reverting to capitalist rule: `` prostitution, drugs, gambling, begging, unemployment, abysmal inequality between citizens ... `` He believes communism is too young a philosophy to give up on, especially when one considers the alternative. This notion, of course, is being rejected by millions of East Europeans who believe it is farfetched to suggest the flaws of Marxism can be corrected, as <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> suggests, with mere fine tuning.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gedda </PERSON> has covered foreign affairs for the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> since 1968.
