<FIRST>r a PM-Jury-Lottery     12-15 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jury-Lottery,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Jury Can Split Lottery Winnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was a case in which the judge had to read the jury its rights _ rights to the $ 1,000 prize from a lottery ticket that came with lunch. The panel, deliberating in a product liability case, was n't sure if it could keep the cash because the government paid for the lunch. So jurors asked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Crabb </PERSON>, who was presiding over the trial. Bailiff <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowe </PERSON> said <PERSON> Crabb </PERSON> laughed and said to instruct the jury that nothing could be done with the ticket until they decided the case being tried. The lunches, which <PERSON> Bowe </PERSON> picked up at a delicatessan, included four `` Instant Cash Match'' tickets as a promotion, and when a juror scratched the tickets, one was a $ 1,000 winner. The eight jurors asked to split the prize and on Wednesday, after the case was settled, the judge agreed. She said she relied on the motion picture `` Miracle on 34th Street'' and Christmas spirit for precedent. `` The bailiff gave the jury four unnegotiated tickets which in that state had a negligible value,'' the judge wrote in a decision that had the density if not the weight of an actual judicial ruling. `` Since there was nothing improper about giving uncashed tickets of trivial value to the jury, there is no basis for either the bailiff or the government to try to reassert ownership of the tickets or their proceeds. `` We need not decide which of the jurors has any greater claim to the prize ticket over any of the others. In the best spirit of a jury, the jurors have agreed to share equally in any prize money to which they may be entitled.''
</TEXT>
