<HEAD>Gavel Disappears After Legislators Hammer Out Workers' Comp Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Someone has given Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby a pounding headache by walking off with the wooden gavel he used during a recent special session of the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>. `` Who would have ever thought someone would take the gavel?'' <PERSON> Saralee </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiede </PERSON>, the lieutenant governor's executive assistant, said Thursday. She said the gavel has been missing since legislators left <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> earlier this week after wrapping up the session on workers' compensation revisions. `` I mean, we operate on the honors system here,'' she said. `` It's kind of understood that you do n't make off with the paintings on the wall, you do n't take the bronze busts and you do n't steal the gavel.'' The oak gavel, made by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> prison inmates, is nearly 2 feet long and weighs about 4 pounds. `` It does n't have much monetary value,'' <PERSON> Tiede </PERSON> said. `` However, it has a lot of sentimental value at this point. We thought -LRB- Hobby -RRB- might want to present it to someone.'' <PERSON> Carleton </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sergeant-at-arms, issued a memo to all <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offices Wednesday, asking staff members to look out for the gavel. `` I'm not assuming any of the senators did it,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> chamber is open at times when there is nobody in there. It would have been easy for someone to slip in and take it.'' State Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who opposed the workers' compensation legislation proposed by Hobby, suggested that it was `` was probably stolen by a representative of the insurance industry who wants to enshrine it as a holy object.''
