<HEAD>Refugees Protest Forced Repatriations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with protests in another camp.
Pickup 12th graf pvs, ``We haven't...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 11,000 Vietnamese refugees who may be forced to return to their homeland held protest marches for a third day today and burned an effigy of <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. Meanwhile, the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s governor said no more boat people will be sent home against their will before Christmas. Refugees in six camps around this British colony took part in today's demonstrations, which have widened in scope daily since the forced repatriation of 51 boat people on Tuesday. The protesters are among about 44,000 Vietnamese who have sailed into <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> since June 1988 and are considered illegal `` economic migrants'' unless they can prove they fled their Communist homeland fearing persecution. Nearly 6,800 have been denied refugee status after being screened by immigration officials and face repatriation, compared with slightly more than 700 who have qualified for overseas resettlement. Although the protests have been peaceful, about 100 Vietnamese late Thursday attacked a prison officer with iron bars as he investigated a crowd gathering inside the Chi Ma Wan camp. The officer suffered minor injuries. Today, about 4,000 boat people marched inside the <ORGANIZATION> Whitehead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in the New Territories. About 2,500 others chanted slogans as they marched between huts in the <LOCATION> High </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> reception center next to a rural park, the government said. About 550 boat people staged a sit-in at <ORGANIZATION> Sek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in the New Territories, 3,000 others participated in the third day of protest marches at <ORGANIZATION> Hei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chau </ORGANIZATION> camp on an outlying island, and 1,000 Vietnamese demonstrated at <ORGANIZATION> Sham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Po </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in urban <LOCATION> Kowloon </LOCATION>. A few hundred protested at <LOCATION> Chi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wan </LOCATION>. An effigy of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who has strongly defended the forced repatriation program by this British colony, was burned at the Sham Shui Po protest, a government spokesman said. Governor Sir <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said today that more Vietnamese will be sent back against their will but: `` We have n't got a flight plan before Christmas.'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> acknowledged the program has led to widespread international criticism, saying: `` We certainly face the fact there has been a very emotional reaction against what we've done.'' But he added that none of the critics has put forth a viable alternative to solve the problem posed by the massive influx of boat people. Journalists have not been allowed inside the detention centers in recent weeks, but relief agencies say the atmosphere is tense. `` I think the feeling is that there is a great deal of tension in the camps,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Campion </PERSON> of Refugee Concern <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, an advocacy group for the boat people. `` Whether that is going to spill out or explode remains to be seen.'' About 56,000 Vietnamese are housed in squalid camps in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, but only 4,500 refugees have been resettled so far this year. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> argues returning the refugees home is more humane than keeping them indefinitely in crowded centers that are rife with violence and disease. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has condemned the forced repatriation. The approximately 12,000 boat people in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> who arrived before June 1988 are considered refugees eligible for resettlement.
