<HEAD>Safety Board Announces Hearing on LaGuardia Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said today it will conduct a hearing focusing on <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 rudder trim design and cockpit performance in the crash of a <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> jetliner at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. The four-day hearing is to begin Feb. 13 at the <ORGANIZATION> Penta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON>. The Sept. 20 accident, in which the aircraft skidded off the end of the runway into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> after pilots aborted its takeoff, killed two passengers. The plane lodged on a landing pier and broke into pieces. Board Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON>, who will conduct the hearing, said he expects about 16 witnesses to testify on cockpit crew training and coordination, design and operation of the rudder trim system and other issues. `` As tragic as this accident was, it could have been much worse,'' <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON> said. `` We have mechanical and human performance issues to resolve in the course of this investigation, and the hearing will provide us with valuable information on both issues.'' The board did not announce who the witnesses would be, but surviving crew members often testify at such hearings. `` We may not know until just before the hearing whether they will appear,'' said <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON>. Investigators said the plane's tail rudder, used in steering the airliner, was misaligned despite evidence that the crew made all the proper checks. The pilot reported the plane was drifting to the left before he aborted the takeoff. This focused attention on the trim system that holds the rudder steady during takeoff. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> suspended the pilot's licenses of Capt <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> and co-pilot <PERSON> Constantine </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleissas </PERSON> after the crash for their failure to appear immediately for drug tests and questioning by investigators. The safety board's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> hearing will include a panel of senior <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> staff members and a technical panel of investigators, as well as representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The board, which is an independent federal agency, has no rule-making or enforcement powers. Its findings of probable cause and recommendations will be included in a report to be adopted at a public meeting several months after the hearing, although it can issue urgent recommendations at any time.
