<HEAD>Volcano Hurls Ash Seven Miles High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with today's eruption, picking
up 4th graf pvs, `Ash rose....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Redoubt Volcano hurled a cloud of volcanic ash into the sky again early today, a day after it roared into action, and a pilot reported the gritty ash cloud extended 160 miles from the mountain. Thursday's eruption, the volcano's first activity in 23 years, flung ash seven miles high and prompted the evacuation of seven oil workers. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Richter </PERSON>, a geologist with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey, said Redoubt erupted today from 1:40 a.m. to about 4:30 a.m. `` It was powerful,'' <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> said. `` A pilot reported an ash cloud extending from Redoubt to <LOCATION> Talkeetna </LOCATION> at 3:39,'' he said, adding that there were some reports of flashing lights that probably were caused by glowing lava. <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> said the high-altitude cloud of airborne ash blew past <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> and was falling in less populated areas. He said more eruptions were likely. `` I do n't like to use the word ` normal,' but a group of eruptions is typical of a volcano,'' he said. Thursday's eruption of Redoubt, near the western edge of <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION>, 115 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>, came a day after scientists detected a significant increase in seismic activity, the Geological Survey said. It `` looked like a little cloud rising over the mountain and it just started rising like an atomic bomb when it mushrooms,'' said <PERSON> Kristopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Paull </PERSON>, pilot of an airliner in the area Thursday. Ash rose from 15,000 feet to about 40,000 feet within 10 minutes, said <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON>, who was flying an F-15 jet fighter west of <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. Seven of 11 workers at the <LOCATION> Drift </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> oil storage facility were evacuated as a precaution against flooding from melting snow, said the manager of <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inlet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, operator of the facility. Such flooding occurred when the volcano last erupted in 1966. Manager <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouser </PERSON> said the workers were transported in two airplanes, one of which was at the site for a routine grocery delivery. A helicopter stood by for possible evacuation of the four employees who remained at the site as monitors, he said. A truck driver who was on the Sterling Highway, across the inlet from the volcano, when the eruption occurred said the ash was `` real white and fluffy, almost like a cumulus cloud.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paskievitch </PERSON>, a geologist for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION>, said seismic activity beneath the volcano returned to normal soon after the eruption. He said it was impossible to predict whether more eruptions would occur. The <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> said a light dusting of ash was observed in the <LOCATION> Wasilla </LOCATION> area, about 40 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>, shortly after noon Thursday. Redoubt Volcano is within the <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> and Preserve and has been active at least four times during this century.
