<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's high court today overturned convictions imposed in a controversial treason trial and set free five black activists, three of them senior anti-apartheid leaders jailed since 1985. `` It's fantastic, because now justice has been vindicated,'' said Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, when he and other supporters were told the five men were being flown from their island prison in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. The three leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and one of their co-defendants, a church worker, were convicted of treason in November 1988 after a three-year trial. Their sentences ranged from six to 12 years. The Appeal Court in <LOCATION> Bloemfontein </LOCATION> overturned the verdicts of those four and seven co-defendants convicted of terrorism. One of the seven, who was serving a five-year term, was freed. The others had received suspended sentences. The Appeal Court accepted defense lawyers' arguments that the trial judge, <PERSON> Kees </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dijkhorst </PERSON>, improperly dismissed one of the two legal experts assisting him in the trial. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dijkhorst </PERSON> had said the law professor, W.A. <PERSON> Joubert </PERSON>, was too sympathetic to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> because he had signed a UDF-supported petition opposing a new constitition that entrenched racially segregated politics. During the trial, most of the defendants were granted bail. But <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dijkhorst </PERSON> repeatedly denied bail requests by the three leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a huge multiracial