<HEAD>Global Flag Gets Start in St. Louis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There are flags for nations, states, cities, clubs and teams, but until now there was no flag for the whole world. `` Heck, <ORGANIZATION> McDonalds </ORGANIZATION>' even has a flag,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Roffmann </PERSON>, one of two <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> men who have designed a `` Global Flag.'' <PERSON> Roffmann </PERSON> said Thursday that he hoped to have the flag flying over every country of the world by the end of 1992 to remind people that they are all `` citizens'' of the planet <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. `` Seeing ourselves as one planet _ no divisions, no boundaries _ helps us envision the new levels of cooperation and interdependence we need as we move into the most critical decade of human history,'' <PERSON> Roffmann </PERSON> said. `` Our survival depends on our ability to think globally and act locally,'' he said. The 3-by-5 Global Flag is midnight blue, and in the center is a full-color reproduction of the `` full earth'' photograph taken by Apollo 17 en route to the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roffmann </PERSON> said he and his partner, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>, already had arranged to have the flag flying at the Global Forum on Environment and Development for Survival and the Soviet-American Citizens' Summit, both in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> next month They also hope to have it incorporated into World Peace Day activities around the world on Dec. 31, as well as the global Earth Day 1990, on April 22. `` It would be marvelous if the next time we go to the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>, instead of planting the American flag, we planted this global flag,'' <PERSON> Roffmann </PERSON> said. In the first few weeks of their project, <PERSON> Roffmann </PERSON> said, about 100 Global Flags have been distributed to people and organizations. A portion of the proceeds from the sale of the flags, which run about $ 50, will go to organizations involved in Campaign for the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, a 10-year campaign to create a peaceful, sustainable world that will kick off Dec. 31.
