ery reliable,'' she said. Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadner </PERSON> declined to comment on the case but indicated that his office would not rule out the use of DNA typing in future prosecutions. `` What happened in the <PERSON> McLeod </PERSON> case is in no way a reflection on the future of DNA testing, and any assertions to the contrary are taking advantage of a unique situation,'' <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said. DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, is a complex molecule found mainly in the nucleus of living cells and plays a vital role in heredity. Because it contains genetic information unique to each individual, it has been used by forensic researchers to positively identify suspects in criminal cases. Developed in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, DNA typing was accepted as evidence for the first time in this country last year in a criminal trial in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Since then, DNA evidence has been used in at least 100 criminal cases, mostly rape and murder prosecutions, in 23 states. Similar quality control problems at <ORGANIZATION> Lifecodes </ORGANIZATION> led a court in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to reject part of a DNA test as evidence in a murder trial last year. <ORGANIZATION> Lifecodes </ORGANIZATION> subsequently said it had solved its quality control problems.
