<FIRST>u i AM-Sakharov-Gorbachev     12-15 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov-Gorbachev,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov-Gorbachev Relationship Defined Era of Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Sakharov, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> shared little personally except a mutual respect and a commitment to change. As they went before the nation in a parliamentary session this week, they could not have appeared more different: <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, at the pinnacle of his power, was robust and self-confident; <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was stooped and stammering. And yet, the times dictated that they work together, and it was <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s relationship to the Soviet president that defined his role in an era of reform. It was a sign of the program of change that <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> long had urged and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> instituted that Soviets could watch the two men struggle with each other at the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies parliament. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> died Thursday evening in his study, preparing to challenge <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> once more on the political supremacy of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> leads. `` It's a great loss,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said Friday during a break in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> had served as a parliamentarian. `` During this time of perestroika, <PERSON> Academician </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> had his mission, his role, and that we all understood. He was a man of conviction and sincerity. He was not some sort of political intriguer.'' The Soviet public liked and respected <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> at least as much as <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. An unscientific poll conducted by the weekly Arguments and Facts in October found <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> the country's most popular politician, more popular than <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> freed <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> from the exile in the industrial city of Gorky imposed by <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, and withdrew Soviet soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. It was <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s criticism of the intervention into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> 10 years ago that led to his exile in <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION>. Even though <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> owed his return to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from the living hell of isolation, force-feedings and surveillance in <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> never dominated <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> spoke out in favor of the reforms <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> instituted because they matched his own ideals, but in the past several months had become increasingly critical of the pace of the reform and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s accumulation of power. He said the country had no alternative to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s leadership but prodded the Soviet president to push harder. The day he died, he told a group of like-minded deputies that the Soviet leadership's hesitancy to press more radical reform was leading the country to catastrophe. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> told the first <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in June: `` I personally respect <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergeyevich </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> very much, but it is dangerous to give so much power even to the initiator of perestroika.'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> continually challenged <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but was no match as a public speaker to the vigorous and self-confident presi