<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 King County officials are considering a proposal that could bring growth in the nation's hottest housing market to a grinding halt. The proposal, unveiled Thursday by County Councilman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, would block housing construction in unincorporated <LOCATION> King </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> until after adequate roads, schools and other services are built. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> and co-sponsor Councilwoman <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said the proposal aims to shift the power to make land use decisions to the public, essentially giving them veto rights over developments if their neighborhoods are being overwhelmed by growth. In May, <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> voters adopted limits on downtown growth in one of the city's first demonstrations of discontent with the fast pace of development. If the county council approves the measure, it would put an amendment of the council's charter on the Nov. 6, 1990, general election ballot. The proposed amendment reads: `` No county officials shall have the authority to approve private development where facilities will not be adequate, unless an emergency is found to exist.'' That would eliminate the discretion county officials have to approve development plans when services are not in place. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> listed roads, sewers, water, schools, open space and surface water drainage as key services that would have to be in place before ground is broken for a project. `` We're taking away the permissiveness that has allowed growth to occur before we have the infrastructure to support it,'' <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said. He said he would formally introduce the ordinance at Monday's council meeting A simple majority on the nine-member council is needed for approval. `` What it does is require communities to ` pay as they grow' and that's something we've been promoting for over a year,'' said newly elected council member <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Derdowski </PERSON>, a slow-growth activist. Developers criticized the measure as a `` poorly drafted'' ordinance that fails to define what is adequate service. `` If this ordinance passes, -LRB- housing -RRB- prices will skyrocket,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Master </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said a later ordinance would define which services would be included and what would be considered adequate. The measure comes as the median cost of a single-family home in the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> area is rising at 23.7 percent a year, up from $ 88,900 to $ 110,000 in the past year, the fastest pace in the nation, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION>. The population is also swelling, with an estimated 650,000 more people expected by 2020. The 2,128-square-mile county has about 1.4 million residents, about 31 percent of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state's population. Incorporated areas include <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and its suburbs, with a total of about 1 million people. Much of the eastern part of the county is unincorporated. The county has grown by about 190,000 people during the past decade, with newcomers accounting for about half the increase. <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> was named the nation's most liveable city this year by the Places Rated Almanac, in part because of its affordable real estate.
