<HEAD>Opposition's Big Victory Should Help Subdue Pinochet</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A decisive election victory gives the new civilian government vital leverage on Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who will keep command of the army after leaving the presidency, but the road ahead is not smooth. President-elect <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> acknowledges he must build careful alliances with conservatives to achieve democratic reforms sought by his center-left alliance. Also, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> appears at least indirectly strengthened in his claim to leadership of the politial right. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> won 55.2 percent of the vote for president Thursday, nearly twice the 29.4 percent of pro-government candidate <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchi </PERSON>. A third candidate, entrepreneur <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Errazuriz </PERSON>, got only 15.4 percent, according to virtually complete returns released Friday. The 17-party coalition <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> represents won a majority in the 120-member <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> and 22 of the 38 elected <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats. The consitution <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s government wrote in 1980, however, allows it to appoint up to 10 more senators. His own impressive victory, and the especially good showing of his <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Demcratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> give <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> `` a strong mandate,'' said <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Valenzuela </PERSON>, Latin American studies director at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Thursday's vote demonstrates that `` <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> has broad-based support, which <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> does not,'' <PERSON> Valenzuela </PERSON> said in an interview in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, where he witnessed the election. `` He can say: ` Look, I got 55 percent. You only got 43 percent.''' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> won 43 percent of the vote in October 1988 on a referendum proposal to extend his presidency to 1997. He lost the referendum and was forced to call the elections, but <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s showing was much stronger than <PERSON> Buchi </PERSON>'s in the presidential race. `` For the right, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> is the most powerful figure, potentially,'' <PERSON> Valenzuela </PERSON> said. The fiercely anti-communist general, 74, seized power in 1973, overthrowing elected President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, an avowed Marxist who died in the coup. He is to relinquish the presidency March 11, but has said he will remain as commander of the 60,000-man army. A special clause in the constitution allows him to keep the job until 1998. From the army command, directly across <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>'s main boulevard from the presidential palace, he plans to lead the military in its role as watchdog of his 1980 constitution. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> also has hinted occasionally that he may return to politics _ because, the general says, Chileans will come to miss his authoritarian leadership. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>'s platform includes several democratic changes in the constitution and in special laws, but majorities of up to two-thirds are needed to pass them. That his coalition failed to achieve such dominance is due largely to complicated electoral laws written by the junta that caused many leftist candidates to lose even when they got more votes than rightist opponents. Parties of the left have considerable influence in powerful labor groups, and <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> will need to make sure they do not feel disenfranchized as he tries to reach accommodation with conservatives. At a news conference Friday, the president-elect seemed well aware of his delicate position. He denied any intention of setting his <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> apart from the alliance as a means of wooing moderate rightists known to dislike <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. The alliance will continue to work `` as a team,'' <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> said, and he will follow a `` path of broad consensus'' between now and March 11. He spoke of the peaceful manner in which Chileans are returning to civilian government, and declared: `` In this country, the commitment toward moderation prevails.''
