<HEAD>Fire At High-Rise for Elderly Kills Three</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with number of dead and injured
confirmed, authorities saying arson is cause and that safety violation
helped fire spread; picks up 8th graf, `There's not....'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An arson blaze this morning on the first floor of a high-rise for the elderly pumped smoke into upper floors, killing three people out of reach of firefighters' aerial ladders, authorities said. After rescuers evacuated the 15-story Midtown Towers in below-zero cold, 77 residents and two firefighters were taken to <LOCATION> Watertown </LOCATION>'s two hospitals, most for treatment of smoke inhalation. Six residents were listed in critical condition. `` A lot of people were hanging out the upstairs windows screaming,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Guilfoyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ambulance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` There was a tremendous amount of flames coming out the front and back end of the building.'' Fire Chief <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gravelle </PERSON> said a door at the base of the building's stairwell jammed, trapping some residents until it was pried open. Most of the dead and injured were reportedly found in stairwells, he said. State fire investigators classified the fire as `` probable arson,'' Police Chief <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hennegan </PERSON> said. He said if this preliminary determination stands, the deaths will be investigated as homicides. Investigators said the fire started shortly after midnight in a first-floor recreation area of the 20-year-old building, which has 150 apartments. More than 100 firefighters from nine departments arrived within minutes and controlled the blaze within an hour. <PERSON> Gravelle </PERSON> said the fire was contained to the first floor, but that smoke quickly spread throughout the building. He said a safety violations helped the fire spread on the first floor _ the recreation room's double doors were left open overnight. One of the dead was found in a hallway and two were found in stairwells on the 12th and 13th floors, beyond the reach of the city's aerial ladders. `` There's not a truck in the world that could reach the top of the building,'' said former <LOCATION> Watertown </LOCATION> Fire Chief <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Damon </PERSON>, adding that the fire truck ladders reach about eight stories. Firefighters led about 200 elderly residents down fire-protective staircases out of the building or through apartment windows to a suspended aerial platform. A shelter was set up nearby for those residents not requiring medical treatment. `` I was asleep with my TV on, and all of a sudden the smoke alarm went on and I got right up,'' said 78-year-old <PERSON> Edna </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>. Police Sgt. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Montrois </PERSON> identified the dead as <PERSON> Pansy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiernan </PERSON> 88, <PERSON> Eunice </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, 88 and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepe </PERSON>, 69, all residents.
