<FIRST>r w AM-IndustrialProduction     12-15 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Industrial Production,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Output Little Changed As Sluggishness Spreads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Industrial production was little changed in November despite rebounding from a major strike and a devestating earthquake, the government said Friday in a report that showed spreading economic sluggishness. Many economists said the weak 0.1 percent gain in output _ the first in three months _ accompanied by moderating inflation suggests the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> should permit another drop in short-term interest rates to stimulate the economy. `` Manufacturing production continues to slow _ it's not collapsing, but it is slowing _ and I think the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is sensing that it has some type of leeway to ease'' rates, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Silvia </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Kemper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. In its report Friday on industrial production, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> attributed the gain to a rebound from the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> strike, which ended in late November, and from the lingering effects in the computer and related industries from the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay-area </LOCATION> earthquake in October, when output had slumped 0.6 percent. `` Excluding the impact of these events, the total index would have been little changed in both October and November.'' the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> reported. The manufacturing sector has been among the hardest hit by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s tight-money policies as the central bank tries to contain inflation by slowing the economy without tipping it into a recession. But in the latest report on inflation, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that wholesale prices dipped 0.1 percent in November, the third decline in five months. Industrial output had not risen since a 0.4 percent gain last August and that followed a 0.1 percent drop in July. It was down 0.3 percent in September. `` Clearly, the manufacturing sector is sluggish,'' contended <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON>, senior economic adviser for the <ORGANIZATION> WEFA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> `` It started in the auto industry earlier this year and spread to other consumer durables,'' he said. `` We're seeing softness in appliances and furniture and, in the last month or so, seeing it show up in the capital goods industry.'' Output at manufacturing plants making both durable and nondurable goods rose 0.2 percent in November after falling 0.8 percent in October and 0.4 percent in September. Production of durable goods _ items expected to last more than three years _ rose 0.5 percent last month after falling 1.8 percent in October and 0.7 percent in September. Nondurable manufacturing fell 0.2 percent after rising 0.5 percent in October and 0.1 percent in September. In another report reflecting sluggishness, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said the operating rate of the nation's factories, mines and utilities edged down 0.1 percentage point to 82.7 percent in November to its lowest rate since April 1988. `` That's one of the reasons you're seeing producer prices falling,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratajczak </PERSON>, economic forecasting director at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` When you have excess capacity, that's when you see price concessions. The closer <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry gets to full operating capacity, the greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand, leading to shortages and subsequent price increases. Analysts generally consider an operating rate of 85 percent or above as an indication of inflationary pressures. Factory use had dipped in October to 82.8 percent from 83.4 percent in September. The rate posted 10-year highs of 84.3 percent last December and January.
</TEXT>
