<TEXT>
 `` I personally respect <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergeyevich </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> very much, but it is dangerous to give so much power even to the initiator of perestroika,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in June after it added the presidency to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s job as party general secretary. He said he had no regrets about the difficult path he had followed. `` I am proud of this exile in Gorky like a medal I wear,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was born May 21, 1921, in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, and like his father became a physicist. He was inducted into the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> in 1953 at age 32, the youngest member ever. In 1948, he joined physicist <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Tamm </PERSON> in developing the hydrogen bomb and for the next 20 years lived in secrecy with a good apartment, driver, high salary and government awards. But, like <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> began to worry about the morality of developing weapons of mass destruction. He had his first major brush with the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> in 1961, when he appealed to Premier <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> to stop testing nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> responded that scientists should n't meddle in politics. Two years later, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed to such limits in a treaty with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, horrified at Soviet society's mistreatment of its citizens, said his `` social and political views underwent a major evolution.'' He risked his status and began using his influence for victims of human rights abuses in 1966. The authorities showed their rage in 1968, when <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s `` Progress, Co-existence and Intellectual Freedom'' was published abroad It called for Soviet-American detente long before the concept became part of Soviet foreign policy. He was banned from work on secret projects. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> called the essay `` a turning point in my life'' and two years later he helped found the <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. After the 1968 death of his first wife, <PERSON> Klavdia </PERSON>, he married <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> in 1971, and she became his constant companion. He spoke out against repression of dissidents and for democratic reforms. His cluttered one-bedroom apartment became a mecca for troubled Soviets: Crimean Tatars, Volga Germans, political prisoners, religious believers and refuseniks _ Jews denied permission to emigrate. In awarding him the peace prize in 1975, the <ORGANIZATION> Nobel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> called him `` the conscience of contemporary mankind.'' By 1980, the authorities had had enough. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> condemned the Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in an American TV interview and on Jan. 22, 1980, <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents seized him on a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> street. Without charges or a trial, he was exiled to <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION>, 250 miles east of the capital, and stripped of his awards. The once-respected scientist spent nearly seven years in the remote city with <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> guards trailing him, searching his apartment and secretly filming him. He was cut off from the world. Despite heart trouble, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was drugged and tied to a bed and force-fed during a hunger strike. `` We wo n't let you die, but we will make you an invalid,'' a doctor warned him. Western governments, scientific and human rights groups pressed the Soviets to release <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>. Then in December 1986, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> phoned to say he could return to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, restraining his joy at the news to show his concern for others, told <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to free all political prisoners. Two months after <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s release, scores of political prisoners were freed and he threw his support behind <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. He got his old job back at the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> and in November 1988 was allowed to travel abroad for the first time, even though <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had said <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> could not go to other countries because he knew state secrets. Survivors include a son and two daughters from his first marriage, as well as <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON>'s children from a previous marriage: son, <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Semyonov </PERSON>, and daughter, <PERSON> Tatiana </PERSON>, who is married to <PERSON> Yefrem </PERSON> <PERSON> Yankelevich </PERSON>.
