cus, symbol, the spokesman of freedom in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said he was glad <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> lived long enough `` to see substantial progress in the direction which he was pointing his country toward.'' `` And I think in remembering that today we must also express the hope that the torch will be handed on and that work which is not yet completed will be carried forward by people who will rembmer him,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> added. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> called <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> `` a tremendous force for peace and freedom.'' `` He was as well a courageous pioneer who led the way in the face of great adversity and we are very sad by his passing,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` I think <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> would be pleased if our reflection on his work extended as well to all of those brave men and women, many of them whose names we'll never know, who sacrificed their liberty, indeed their lives, for the freedom of others.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said until the very end, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> pursued `` the causes that meant the very most to him, standing up in parliament for beliefs that may not be fully accepted today, but which will have their day.''
