<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ca n't guarantee pilots wo n't drop bombs outside designated central <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> target ranges, the military said Friday as cleanup of stray bombs on public lands was suspended for the winter. `` Nobody could say that it wo n't happen again,'' said <PERSON> Olin </PERSON> <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Fallon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's malfunction of equipment that could happen ... And there's always human error.'' Capt. <PERSON> Rex </PERSON> <PERSON> Rackowitz </PERSON>, commanding officer at <PERSON> Fallon </PERSON> where the nation's fighter pilots train, has said bombs and rockets might have landed outside fenced ranges for the past 30 years because of pilot or equipment error. Or, he has said, they could have skipped along the desert floor after failing to explode upon impact. Bombs, duds and shrapnel that landed as much as one mile outside ranges were being removed or blown up on site in a seven-week cleanup exercise codenamed `` Operation Ugly Baby.'' The ranges begin 60 miles east of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>. There are plans to keep some 110,000 acres surrounding the Bravo 16, 17 and 19 ranges closed to the public through the winter in case undiscovered ordnance remains, <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. A team of 150 Explosive Ordnance Disposal personnel flown to <PERSON> Fallon </PERSON> to help with the exercise were going home Friday, <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> said. There are no definite plans to enlist such a large group again to help clear away stray bombs, he added. `` It would be misleading to indicate we were finished with this thing,'' <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> said. `` We'll keep plugging away at it, relying on the assets at our base. But basically, we only have five EODs at <PERSON> Fallon </PERSON> permanantly and they have to work on the ranges, too.'' <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> said he expects all the red flagged bombs to be destroyed Friday so the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> does n't leave ordnance exposed during the winter, although people wo n't have access to the lands normally used for hiking, hunting, grazing and off-road vehicles. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sought indefinite closure of the 110,000 acres of land surrounding the bombing ranges because of fears buried ordnance remains undetected and could blow up if disturbed by people or animals. The land will be reopened next summer and ca n't be permanantly closed without congressional approval, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. No injuries have been reported from public contact with any stray bombs, according to <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> who said the cleanup exercise went safely. He said one <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> worker hurt his leg when he fell down a hill, but no other injuries were reported during the sweeps for bombs <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> did n't have statistics on the total amount of ordnance discovered during the exercise that cost the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> several hundred thousand dollars. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> recovered more than 2,000 bombs and duds from its Bravo 17 range alone. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> was cited by the state of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> for improper disposal procedures of hazardous waste and for failing to notify the state of the cleanup effort that began secretly in October. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> faces fines of up to $ 10,000 a day per violation if found guilty.
