<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranians braved rain and cold in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and five other cities Friday to choose nine <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> members in elections considered a crucial test for President <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s pragmatic policies. Hard-liners fear <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s efforts to liberalize the economy and Iranian society will undermine revolutionary fervor and the ideological purity of the late <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, said turnout in five of the six constituencies, including <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, was so great that the 5 o'clock closing time of the polls was extended by two hours. But observers in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> reported low voter turnout. An <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> diplomat based in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> said the 5 p.m. closing time of the polls was extended to attract last-minute voters in an effort to increase the count. The radio did not provide a figure for voter turnout. But the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, also monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, said all constituents over 15 were eligible to vote. Candidates chosen by the electorate will represent <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kashan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Karaj </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kerman </LOCATION>, Bandar-Turkman-Kordkui and <LOCATION> Kuhdasht-Chegini </LOCATION> in Parliament. Some of the constituencies are multi-member. Four seats in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> were being contested by 38 candidates, many of them hard-line opponents of <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> and his so-called pragmatic policies. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s former seat in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, which he won with a record 1.2 million votes in the last general election in April-May 1988, is one of those vacant. He gave up that seat following his victory in the presidential elections in June. Most of the other vacant seats in the 270-member Majlis, or parliament, were left empty when <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> appointed legislators to posts in his new administration. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s ambitious policies to revive the economy by improving ties with the West to attract badly needed investment and technology are under attack by a hard-line faction led by former Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>, who is contesting one of the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> seats, was dumped in August when <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> formed his new government. He is closely linked with Shiite Moslem extremists believed to hold most of the 18 Western hostages _ including eight Americans _ in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. He was also involved with militants who carried out suicide bombings against the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> base in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in 1983, killing hundreds of people. Friday's elections are <PERSON> Montashemi </PERSON>'s first major effort to make a comeback. The Majlis is already dominated by radicals of various stripes and further gains by hard-liners in the elections will intensify pressure on <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> has been very low-key about the elections. He said Friday after casting his vote that `` these are not the general elections, therefore they lack enthusiasm. But in any case, they are effective.'' His remarks were broadcast on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> TV, monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, who died June 3, spent much of his time after the 1979 revolution mediating squabbles between hard-liners and pragmatists, and keeping their power in check. The power struggle has intensified since <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> became president and began sidelining his opponents. Apart from <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>, a number of other ex-ministers dumped by <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> are standing in the election. This includes former Labor Minister <PERSON> Abulqasem </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarhadizadeh </PERSON>, former Education Minister <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Akrani </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Heavy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Behzad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabavi </PERSON>, former Commerce Minister <PERSON> Habibollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Asgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Owladi </PERSON>, and former Posts and Telegraph Minister <PERSON> Morteza </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabavi </PERSON>.
