<HEAD>Party Draft Calls for Multiparty System, Membership in the EC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Party proposed a multiparty system, free elections and full membership in Western economic institutions, including the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, according to a declaration drafted Friday. `` The end to the authoritiarian socialism has come,'' said the declaration, which also called for constitutional guarantees to bring market-oriented economic reform, establish an independent judiciary and protect human rights. The document, prepared for adoption at next month's national party congress and published by the <ORGANIZATION> Borba </ORGANIZATION> daily, appears to be <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s reply to the wave of democratic reforms currently sweeping <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` The communist party of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> supports freedom of assembly, speech and all other civil liberties, regardless of political convictions of individuals,'' said the document released by a preparatory committee. Political `` associations, movements or parties will depend on the will of the citizens, whose freedom of choice must be guaranteed by the constitution,'' the declaration stated. It said that the communist party will no longer retain its monopoly on power and will participate along with other parties in `` free, direct and secret elections.'' `` We are changing all of this now in order that tomorrow will not be too late for socialism in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>,'' the document stated, adding that the reforms should be implemented within six months after the congress. Until now, the Communist leadership of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s largest republic of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> was the staunchest opponent of Western-style democracy in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. But at its congress on Friday <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> appeared to have softened its hard-line stance Communists and Serbian authorities `` have no reason or wish to administratively impede the establishment of -LRB- independent -RRB- political parties'' in the republic, said <PERSON> Bogdan </PERSON> <PERSON> Trifunovic </PERSON>, the region's party chief, in his keynote address. <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s rejection of Western-style democracy has been shared to date by <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s military, which contended that opposition parties would be formed along ethnic lines, thus fueling ethnic tensions. However, Gen. <PERSON> Ivo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tominc </PERSON> on Friday was quoted by the official <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency as saying that `` the army would not stand in the way of the country's democratic development'' and that it would `` adjust itself to the changes in the society.'' The second-largest republic of <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> and liberal northern <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> have already endorsed parliamentary democracy and are both scheduled to hold free legeslative elections next spring. Independent movements and parties have been formed in <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> in the past year. Despite resistance from authorities several opposition groups have also sprung up in <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bosnia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Macedonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>, where Communists have in the past tried to sidestep democratic reforms. The draft congress declaration also said <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> will seek `` full participation in integration processes in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and membership in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and other similar organizations and institutions.'' <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has for years been a socialist showcase despite its one-party system. But political, economic, social and ethnic problems have mushroomed since the death in 1980 of President <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, whose charisma was seen as a major force in bounding together the divergent ethnic groups in the country. In an unprecedented move, <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> last month severed all business and political ties with <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> after authorities there banned an anti-Slovenian rally planned by thousands of Serbs. The Serbian move was generally seen as an attempt to isolate <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> and prevent its liberal ideas from spreading all over the rest of the country. `` The economic blockade of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> ... is contrary to the implementation of economic and political reforms and the reform of the party in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>,'' said Gen. <PERSON> Tominc </PERSON> in the first open army criticism of the <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> move, according to <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION>.
