<FIRST>r w AM-WetlandsMemorandum     12-15 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wetlands Memorandum,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Decides To Put Hold On EPA-Corps Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An agreement between the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> that would have begun to carry out President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign pledge to preserve wetlands will be held up for 30 days, the administration announced Friday. The two agencies `` will use the extension to allow for explanations and discussion with federal agencies that have raised concerns about the agreement,'' and to `` clear up any misunderstandings about the purpose of the memorandum,'' <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The memorandum of agreement, which was reached in early November and scheduled to take effect Friday, has caused a split within the administration. The departments of Energy and Transportation oppose the agreement and the Council on Environmental Quality and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> are in favor. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> denied reports that the agreement had sparked a fight in the department between the Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Minerals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> said `` The only concerns we have are procedural.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had promised during the campaign to strive for a goal of `` no net loss'' of wetlands. In a letter to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> said the way in which the White House handles the EPA-Corps agreement `` will demonstrate whether or not you are truly commited to a national wetland policy of no net loss.'' `` There is no middle ground on this one. It's either up or down,'' wrote <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Hair </PERSON>. The agreement has faced stiff criticism from the oil industry in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> congressional delegation, who fear it could disrupt oil and gas production on the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Slope </LOCATION> and cripple that state's economy. Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> has threatened to sue if the agreement is n't changed. Many conservationists have grown increasingly concerned about the disappearance of wetlands such as swamps, bogs, marshes, potholes on the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and tidal estuaries. According to some estimates, up to 400,000 acres of wetlands per year have been lost in recent decades to housing devlopments, farms, shopping centers, highways and other encroachments of a modern economy. But wetlands buffer floods, purify streams and provide wildlife habitat for many species that ca n't life elsewhere. Federal law requires that the Corps grant a permit before developers may put fill in most wetlands. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> may challenge the decision and has certain veto powers over it, and the two agencies frequently had been at odds. The <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> agreed in the memorandum to `` strive to avoid adverse impacts and offset unavoidable adverse impacts to existing aquatic resources, and for wetlands, will strive to acheive a goal of no overall net loss of values and functions.'' The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, in its statement, said the memorandum `` does not define a ` no net loss' policy, but rather establishes a clear sequence of actions to be considered in the -LRB- existing -RRB- permit-review process.'' Under the agreement, permit applicants would first have to seek alternatives to disturbing wetlands and if none were available would have to work to minimize damege to wetlands. If the project would still cause significant harm, the applicant would have to compensate for the loss, perhaps by building new wetlands or restoring, old, already damaged areas.
