<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A circuit judge has ruled that the city's year-old loitering ordinance, aimed at street drug dealers, is unconstitutional The law is vague and overbroad, and violates the Fourth and 14th Amendments of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution, <ORGANIZATION> Brevard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoon </PERSON> decided this week. The Fourth Amendment gives citizens rights against unreasonable search and seizure and the 14th Amendment guarantees the right to due process for any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen. The ordinance, adopted in December 1988, made it unlawful to loiter in or near <LOCATION> Melbourne </LOCATION>'s streets or public places in a manner for engaging in drug-related activities. <LOCATION> Melbourne </LOCATION> city officials stand by the law, which was closely modeled after a long-standing ordinance adopted in <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, that had withstood scrutiny. `` We would n't have adopted the ordinance if we had not felt it would meet that test,'' City Manager <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Halter </PERSON> said Thursday. City Attorney <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinman </PERSON> plans to meet with Brevard-Seminole State Attorney <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfinger </PERSON> within the next week to discuss an appeal, <PERSON> Halter </PERSON> said. Only one person had been charged under the ordinance, and the case against him was dropped when the officer who arrested the man left the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and failed to appear in court, <PERSON> Halter </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Antoon </PERSON> wrote in his order: `` While the city has passed this legislation with the noble goal of reducing drug-related crime, it has also given law enforcement and the state ` carte blanche' authority to prosecute innocent people exercising fundamental, personal liberties.
