<HEAD>Havel Calls for Justice, Not Revenge Against Communists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opposition activist <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> said Friday that if he is elected <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s first non-Communist president in four decades he will try to prevent a Communist witch hunt. `` There must be justice, but not revenge,'' said <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, the playwright and leader of the opposition Civic Forum, in an interview with the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION>. `` I would try my best to avoid a witch hunt in this country. Including Communists.'' His comments followed word of a deepening split inside the ruling party between hard-line and reform-minded members that could lead to the establishment of a new democratic party. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has 1.7 million members, all of them are our compatriots and there are countless people among them who are among the same as we are and who want this country to live in democracy,'' said <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rudolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Prevratil </PERSON>, spokesman for the recently founded reform <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> group <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forum </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> that next week's party congress `` will show whether this movement can live inside the Communist Party.'' Reform members of the party are anxious to distance themselves from the discredited regime of ex-party chief <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> and former hard-line President <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON>, who resigned last Sunday after swearing in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s first government not dominated by Communists in 41 years. Since then, a dispute has developed over how to elect the president. Under the constitution, the president is to be chosen by the parliament within two weeks. But the Communist-dominated <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> is reluctant to vote for <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, and is considering a proposal to throw the election open to popular vote. Negotiations are under way to resolve the dispute between the opposition and leaders of the Communist and other smaller parties. A final resolution is not expected until after <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> reconvenes Dec. 19 and an extraordinary party congress is held next Wednesday and Thursday. The interview with <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> is the first in a series to be conducted by the state news agency, which is moving toward greater independence from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` The real presidential campaign has begun,'' the agency said, adding that interviews would be conducted with all those considered leading contenders. These include <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, architect of the `` Prague Spring'' reforms who was ousted in 1969 after the Soviet invasion; <PERSON> Cestmir </PERSON> <PERSON> Cisar </PERSON>, the student candidate for president in 1968, later expelled from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>; and <PERSON> Ladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s prime minister until Nov. 7. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> said he did not want the race to `` drive a wedge'' between himself and <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> or between Czechs and Slovaks. He said his priority, if elected, would be to `` guard the quiet, peaceful and dignified nature of the social movement, which some call a revolution'' and not let it be sullied by `` intrigue, politicking and all kinds of dirt.''
