<HEAD>FDA Wants To Ban Use Of Word `Hormone' On Skin Product Labels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> wants to prohibit manufacturers from using the word `` hormone'' on the labels of nonprescription skin products. Labeling such as `` hormone cream'' implies that the product has a therapeutic effect by altering the structure or function of the body, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. However, the agency said that while nonprescription skin creams can contain hormones, they are at low levels that have not been shown to have any therapeutic effect. Under the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed ban, manufacturers could not refer to their products as `` hormone creams'' or say they contain `` hormones.'' But they would be allowed to include in their regular listing of ingredients the names of hormones in the product, as long as they are not listed prominently. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has published the proposal in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Register </ORGANIZATION> but a final rule is not expected to be issued for a year, a spokeswoman said. The ban would take effect six months after the final rule is published, but the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is asking manufacturers to comply voluntarily with the proposal before the rule becomes final.
