<HEAD>Governor Says Development Should Accompany New Freeway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last link of a $ 675 million freeway has opened, more than 30 years after its proposal set off years of bickering and court fights. The final link of the <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuther </PERSON> Freeway opened to a flood of cars Thursday evening. <PERSON> Reuther </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickmeyer </PERSON>, and the man who originally proposed Interstate 696, former highway director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackie </PERSON>, attended the ceremony. <PERSON> Reuther </PERSON>, a former president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union, died in a 1970 plane crash. The final 9.1-mile section was finished this month and was the last link of the 28.2-mile, $ 675 million freeway. The road is expected to carry more than 100,000 vehicles daily at first with that number growing to 170,000 daily, cutting east-west travel time north of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> by as much as 30 minutes, state officials said. Interstate 696, which borders 16 cities, was first proposed in 1957. But the section between Interstate 75 and <LOCATION> Lahser </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> had to go through seven communities, and it was up to them to decide which routes to choose among five or six alternatives. They could n't agree, according to <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Garceau </PERSON>, deputy district engineer for the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> In 1966, then-Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Romney </PERSON> held a marathon meeting with the seven communities, but they still could n't agree. Binding arbitration upheld court challenges from the disgruntled communities and eventually settled the route in 1968. But then the federal Environmental Protection Act of 1969, which required environmental impact statements, further delayed bid-letting on the last part of the freeway just completed. Land acquisition alone cost $ 81 million.
