<UNK>City Will Test Bodies For Disease And Warn Contacts</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An AIDS test will be routinely performed as part of all autopsies in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, and the information will be used to warn contacts of the deceased who may be at risk, health officials said Friday. They emphasized that the identity of any body that tests positive for HIV, the AIDS virus, would be kept confidential, as required by the state's AIDS Confidentiality Law. Thus the medical examiner's office will not report names of AIDS-positive corpses to the city <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. But it will pass on such information as sex, race, age and neighborhood to help studies of how and where the incurable disease is spreading, said Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>, the chief medical examiner. The only people to know names will be counselors who follow up to warn sex or drug-abusing partners of the AIDS-positive dead that they may have been exposed. The counselors will be trained and made available to <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> by the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, but will be under <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>'s command, said Dr. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, city health commissioner. <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>'s office estimated that at least 1,000 of the approximately 8,000 post mortems performed annually will turn up HIV infection. About 75,000 people die each year in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, but the medical examiner takes jurisdiction only in cases when deaths are violent, suspicious, unexplained or occur without a doctor in attendance. The AIDS testing will be put into effect at the medical examiner's offices soon, after meetings with various AIDS advocacy groups, said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Borakove </PERSON>, speaking for <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>. The groups, representing racial, ethnic and social populations hardest hit by AIDS, have generally resisted, on privacy grounds, any forms of involuntary testing or disclosure. `` We're going to reserve comment until we find out just how it is going to work,'' said <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Knox </PERSON>, spokesman for the Gay Men's Health Crisis <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> developed the plan with <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> and said he could see no sane reason to oppose it. `` What argument can anyone make to not warn the unsuspecting partner of someone who is dead?'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>. He and <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> both have said that because of recent gains in treating the disease, infected people reached early enough may expect longer and better lives.
