tions and employees to `` reject directives and instructions, which are null and void, from those who deal with the occupiers,'' meaning the Syrians. The reference was to <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON>'s government, which is <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and most other governments support. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> became head of a Christian government after President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>'s term ended in September 1988 with <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> unable to agree on a successor. <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> led a competing Moslem Cabinet until the peace plan was worked out. In defiance of <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> remains in his bunker beneath the shell-battered presidential palace at <LOCATION> Baabda </LOCATION>, a Christian suburb east of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, and commands about 20,000 Christian troopers. In his televised appeal, <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> told Christians he could not guarantee peace `` as long as the secessionist movement led by General <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> exists. We have learned from past experience that wars simply explode without anyone declaring them.'' He called <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, 54, a `` mutineer who is leading the nation toward final partition merely because he is hungry for power.'' Most of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> is controlled by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, whose soldiers are in the country under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and the Syrians fought a six-month artillery war that was ended in September by an Arab League cease-fire. <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lahoud </PERSON>, who commands 22,000 Moslem soldiers, have established temporary headquarters at <LOCATION> Ablah </LOCATION> in the Syrian-controlled <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> of eastern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.
