<HEAD>Private Researcher Criticizes Pesticide Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A widely circulated report by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on pesticides used by farmers included information that was deficient, out-of-date and in some respects one-sided, a private researcher said Friday. However, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gianessi </PERSON> of the Washington-based non-profit Resources for the Future said that despite what he perceived as shortcomings, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> report issued Sept. 7 `` makes an important contribution to the debate'' over the use of chemical pesticides. `` Perhaps my expectation was that it would provide answers to most of these questions as well. It does n't,'' he said. `` It probably should be viewed as an important first try to get on top of this issue and not as the final word.'' The 450-page <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> report cited case studies of farmers using alternative methods of production without the indiscriminate use of chemicals. Among its many proposals was one for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to revise federal farm policies so that environmentally sound production methods would be encouraged. Environmentalists and many others applauded the report, based on a three-year $ 625,000 study by a 17-member committee. The <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> put up $ 410,000 for the study, and other financing included $ 80,000 from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gianessi </PERSON> presented his paper at a briefing on the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> report held by Resources for the Future, an independent group founded in 1952. Its specialty is research in development, conservation and use of natural resources. In his critique, <PERSON> Gianessi </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> _ a branch of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> _ used case studies that were `` data deficient'' in making its case for alternative ways of producing farm crops and livestock. `` Information is often not presented for such key factors as: How often do these alternative farmers simply abandon fields because they are too weedy? How much pesticide use is there on these farms? The report hints at these questions but does n't provide any real quantified answers,'' he said Also, <PERSON> Gianessi </PERSON> said, the case studies were for the 1986 crop year _ and the report came out in 1989. `` The farms are referred to as if they are currently sustaining their successes for 1986,'' he said. `` One of these farms has gone out of business. At least two others have had to abandon key parts of their successful program because of the emergence of a new pest in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and the withdrawal of a key pesticide in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.''
