<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The high court on Friday threw out convictions imposed in the country's longest treason trial and freed five black activists, including three prominent anti-apartheid leaders jailed since 1985. Scores of jubilant supporters, including Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, welcomed the men as they passed through <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>'s airport en route from <LOCATION> Robben </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> prison to their homes near <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> `` It's a sign we are winning the struggle,'' said <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>. `` We knew that justice would prevail one day.'' The three leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and one of their co-defendants, a church worker, were convicted of treason in November 1988 after a three-year trial. They received sentences ranging from six to 12 years from a judge who contended the front sought to incite anti-government violence. The Appeal Court in <LOCATION> Bloemfontein </LOCATION> overturned the verdicts against those four and seven co-defendants convicted of terrorism. Six of the seven received suspended sentences, but one, <PERSON> Muzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Malindi </PERSON>, was given a five-year term and sent to the <LOCATION> Robben </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> penitentiary. <LOCATION> Malindi </LOCATION> was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Vaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an affiliate of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. Hundreds of chanting well-wishers greeted the five at <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s airport. Police used guard dogs to control the crowd, confiscated banners, and seized film from at least two news photographers. The independent <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> reported that a woman in the welcoming crowd was bitten by a police dog and that the Rev. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesak </PERSON>, an anti-apartheid leader, was arrested when he tried to aid her. Police had no immediate comment. A five-judge appellate panel unanimously upheld defense lawyers' arguments that the trial judge, <PERSON> Kees </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dijkhorst </PERSON>, improperly dismissed one of the two legal experts assisting him in the trial <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dijkhorst </PERSON> asserted that law professor W.A. <PERSON> Joubert </PERSON> was too sympathetic to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> because he had signed a front-supported petition opposing a new constitution that entrenched racially segregated politics. During the trial, most of the defendants were granted bail. But <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dijkhorst </PERSON> repeatedly denied bail for the three leaders of the front, a huge multiracial coalition formed in 1983 to campaign for black political rights. `` We have not sacrificed more than so many others. We do not feel bitter,'' said <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lekota </PERSON>, one of the front leaders, after being carried shoulder-high through the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> airport. `` For us, it does not stop here. It's the beginning of another chapter.'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dijkhorst </PERSON> ruled that the front was a `` revolutionary organization'' that conspired with the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement to provoke violence in black townships in 1984 in a bid to render <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> ungovernable. The front was banned in February 1988, but most of its leaders have circumvented or defied the ban. <PERSON> Lekota </PERSON>, 41, the front's publicity secretary, was sentenced to 12 years in prison; <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Molefe </PERSON>, 37, the front's national secretary, and <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, 41, secretary of the <LOCATION> Transvaal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> branch, were sentenced to 10 years. The Rev. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Manthata </PERSON>, 49, a church field for the South African Council of Churches, was sentenced to six years. `` We always believed in their innocence,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, general secretary of the church council. `` Their conviction and sentencing were examples of the grave miscarriage of justice which the apartheid courts of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> hand down.'' Lawyers for Human Rights, an association of civil rights lawyers, hailed the <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling as `` an excellent victory'' that would help restore the credibility of the South African judiciary. The group urged the government to disclose the cost of `` this abortive prosecution which took years of blundering incompetence to achieve nothing but red faces.'' The trial began in 1985 in the farming town of <LOCATION> Delams </LOCATION> and was shifted to <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. Eleven of the original 22 defendants were acquitted at various stages. One of the activists' lawyers, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>, said the Appeal Court ruling appeared to be based solely on legal questions and doubted it was related to the changing political climate created by President F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>'s easing of curbs on opposition activity. The trial entailed 439 days of court proceedings spread over more than three years. The 368-page indictment named more than 900 alleged co-conspirators, ranging from <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> to African National Congress leader <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Tambo </PERSON>. There were more than 220 witnesses and the official court record contained about 30,000 pages.
