<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators have found no evidence of jury tampering in the murder trial 26 years ago of a fertilizer salesman charged in the slaying of civil rights activist <PERSON> Medgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>. Charges against <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>, a white supremacist who at the time was a salesman in <LOCATION> Greenwood </LOCATION>, were dropped after two all-white <ORGANIZATION> Hinds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> juries were unable to reach verdicts. Allegations of possible jury tampering by a state agency recently were raised. `` So far, there is absolutely no evidence to indicate jury tampering,'' Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON> said Thursday. `` None were contacted. None were even aware that any contact had been made with their employers until after the fact.'' <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON>, who led the jury-tampering investigation into the second, April 1964 trial, said he told a <LOCATION> Hinds </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury his findings Thursday in a closed-door meeting at the courthouse. Prosecutors now will turn their attention to <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>'s first trial earlier in 1964, although no allegations of jury tampering have been raised about that trial. <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>, field director of the state <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>, was shot to death June 12, 1963, outside his home in northwest <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>'s rifle, bearing one of his fingerprints, was found near the Evers home. <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON> contended the rifle had been stolen from him. <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON> said Thursday that prosecutors are still trying to decide if the murder case itself can be reopened and new charges sought. `` My opinion is unless we can have the benefit of the evidence available in 1964 and newly discovered evidence, it would be extremely hard to get around the speedy trial question,'' <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>, 68, now lives in Signal Mountain, <LOCATION> Tenn </LOCATION>. The district attorney's office investigated <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>'s April 1964 trial after a Jackson newspaper reported Oct. 1 that the state <ORGANIZATION> Sovereignty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the state's segregation spy agency, screened potential jurors. `` What was done was the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Sovereignty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- investigator would call up employers and say, ` What can you tell me about this person?''' <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON> said. `` While I consider it extremely unethical for one state agency to be working against state prosecutors, it still is not a crime,'' <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON> said. The commission, formed by the 1956 <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, died after its funding was cut off in 1973. <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON> said he and others in the district attorney's office contacted 11 of the 12 jurors in the second <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON> trial and are seeking the other juror. <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON> said he and investigators talked earlier with former <ORGANIZATION> Sovereignty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Erle </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> and reviewed records <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> kept. The commission's own records are sealed in a vault on orders of the 1977 Legislature. The rifle and all other evidence from the two trials are missing from the <LOCATION> Hinds </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> circuit clerk's office. But <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON> said there's no indication the evidence was stolen. If cases are inactive for many years, the law allows the evidence to be destroyed.
