ay showing the reconstruction of the forward hold, with a gaping hole, and the reconstructed metal container which held the suitcase bomb. <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said significant progress had been made in identifying other contents of the suitcase, including clothing. He said he ordered the Scottish public inquiry now because the police investigation had reached a stage where he thought it would be `` appropriate.'' He did not elaborate, but said the inquiry could be postponed or canceled if criminal proceedings appeared likely. The public inquiry, formally known as a fatal accident inquiry, will be held next year although a date and a presiding judge have not yet been selected, <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said. He confirmed he had requested Swedish permission for Scottish police to remove clothing from <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON>'s Swedish home, reportedly to compare it with the recovered shreds. `` I have at present no intention to seek the extradition of <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Esson </PERSON> would not say how many individuals were under investigation nor whether all were Arabs. Some are in a position where they could be extradited, he said. Scottish police still believe the bomb `` either started or passed through <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport'' where the flight originated, he said. West German police maintain that has not been proven. Unconfirmed news reports have said the suitcase arrived in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> on an Air <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> flight from the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island and was transferred onto the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight without an accompanying passenger. <PERSON> Esson </PERSON> said he believed police will obtain enough evidence to prosecute the bombers, but said `` there are more investigations to be conducted.'' The photographs released Friday were of sections of the plane, painstakingly reconstructed from wreckage scattered over 845 square miles to determine precisely how it was destroyed. The reconstruction was done by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accidents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Branch </ORGANIZATION> based at <LOCATION> Farnborough </LOCATION>, southwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, which will publish a report on its findings in the first half of 1990. One photograph shows the fuselage, including the forward cargo hold area where the suitcase bomb exploded. The section 55 feet long, 27 feet high and 25 feet wide shows a gaping hole. The metal is peeled back, illustrating what investigators called the `` petaled out'' effect produced by the explosion. Another photo shows the reconstructed metal cargo container, with the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> insignia on the side, in which the suitcase had been loaded onto the plane.
