<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, under attack for his handling of the nation's economic crisis, on Friday accepted the resignation of his economy minister and shuffled two other Cabinet posts. In another development, the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> declared a bank holiday Monday to let shaky financial markets settle. By Tuesday, banks and exchange houses will have been closed for three of the past six working days. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Erman </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, an accountant and former provincial treasury secretary, was named to replace Economy Minister <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> served briefly in the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> as a vice president and has been in the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> as minister of health since <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s May 14 election. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s former campaign manager, <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Mera </PERSON> <PERSON> Figueroa </PERSON>, was appointed interior minister to replace <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauza </PERSON>, who was named minister of health. <PERSON> Figueroa </PERSON> is a longtime strategist in <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> `` I have resigned, and if you are looking for scandalous statements, then you have n't gotten to know me very well in five months,'' <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> told reporters. Asked as he walked out of the Treasury Building after noon what he intended to do in the future, <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> replied, `` I'm going to have lunch.'' <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> canceled a news conference Friday evening. Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON> told reporters no other Cabinet changes would be made and the new ministers will be swor