<HEAD>Press Secretary Wants Dinkins Addressed as `Mister'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The raucous news conferences of the <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> era will have a touch more class under his more sedate successor, his press secretary said. To begin with, call him `` Mr. <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>.'' But first, raise your hand! That was the word Friday from <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON>, the press secretary for Mayor-elect <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, as he laid down some `` rules of conduct'' for the City Hall press corps. <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reporter who won a Pulitzer Prize for editorial writing, told reporters that <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> `` places a high value on courtesy and mutual respect'' and would like to be addressed as `` Mr. <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>'' at press conferences. <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> said reporters also should raise their hands when they want to ask questions and be recognized before doing so, rather than blurt them out in competition with other journalists. `` I would be grateful to you if you would please respectfully pose your questions, ` Mr. <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>'. He'll respond to you,'' <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> said at the third in a series of press briefings he has set up during the transition of government from the <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> administration. `` I would appreciate it if you would please try to restrain yourself and not ask out of turn,'' he said. Asked if <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> had complained to him about the way the press asked its questions, <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> said, `` No. He has not.'' <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> said later he did not mind how reporters addressed him. He said he did not know <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> was going to make such a request and had not asked him to do so. However, he said, `` I do think it would be useful if reporters were not discourteous to each other.'' At Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s news conferences, reporters tend to call him `` Mr. <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON>,'' `` Mayor'' or `` Your Honor.'' <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> seemed amused by the whole thing when he learned about the request. `` I wonder what it would have been like if they called me Mr. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON>, like a horse?'' <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said.
