<HEAD>Average Japanese Income Tops U.S.; Still Behind Switzerland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Edits throughout to CLARIFY that figures are per capita calculations
of gross national product.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> national income, figured on the basis of population, rose slightly in 1988 but was far outpaced by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. Per capita income in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year was $ 19,780, compared with $ 18,580 in 1987. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the income rose from $ 15,840 to $ 21,040, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said. The bank gave all incomes in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> arrives at its figures by dividing the value of a country's total production, the gross national product, by its population. Per capita income thus includes people without income, such as children, and non-wage income, such as returns on invstments. The Swiss continued to rank first in per capita income with a 1988 average of $ 27,260, up from $ 21,310 in 1987. <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> ranked lowest among the 152 members of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> with a 1988 annual per capita income of $ 100. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which in 1987 ranked second only to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> in per capita income, was fifth last year, behind <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. The figure for <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> was $ 20,160, while in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> it was $ 20,020. Much of the rise in the Japanese income can be attributed to an increase in the value of the yen in comparison with the dollar, as well as to increased Japanese production. Elsewhere, differences could be linked to shifts in the value of the dollar compared with other currencies. The dollar has been rising in 1989 after a fall that began in 1985. One former <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> economist, who spoke on condition of anonymity, cautioned that the figures should not be taken to reflect living standards. `` In <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, people have to spend 15 percent of their income fighting the climate,'' he said. `` That's not the case in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s per capita income was $ 13,320 for 1988, compared with $ 10,430 the previous year. <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s was $ 19,150, up from $ 15,610. The bank gives no figure on per capita income for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which is not a member country. However, the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> puts it at $ 8,850, well behind $ 12,480 in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and $ 10,140 in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> rank low on the list with an average income of less than a dollar a day _ $ 330 a year. The per capita in the African countries of <LOCATION> Benin </LOCATION> was $ 340 a year and $ 360 a year in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> reported the fastest growth rate: 9 percent between 1986 and 1988, while <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s income grew by only 1.5 percent and <LOCATION> Benin </LOCATION> declined 4.5 percent. That does not take in account such illegal production as drugs and other goods made for the black market, or wages that are unreported to avoid taxes. It has been estimated that this `` underground economy'' can account for as much as a third of some countries' incomes. `` The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> Atlas 1989'' also reported on some quality-of-life elements. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was at the top in life expectancy. A Japanese baby born in 1988 could expect to live to age 78, compared with 77 for a Swiss, French or Swedish baby, 75 for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> baby, 69 for a Soviet and 42 in such poor African countries as <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leone </LOCATION>. Literacy varied widely. <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> reported in 1985 _ the latest figures available _ that only 12 percent to 14 percent of their people could read and write. <ORGANIZATION> Unesco </ORGANIZATION> reports that the literacy rate is 95 percent or higher in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the more prosperous countries of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> reported a 69 percent literacy rate. Many poor countries have reported big jumps in school enrollment between 1970 and 1986: from 56 percent to 80 percent in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and from 7 percent to 50 percent in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION>.
