<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet military budget for next year is 8.2 percent lower than for 1989 and unilateral cutbacks have reduced Soviet armed forces by 256,000 personnel, a senior army officer said Friday. Col. Gen. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Chervov </PERSON> told a news conference that under President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform program `` the image of the armed forces is changing.'' He said military staffs were going ahead with the plan to cut troop strength by 500,000 by 1991. Plans for the cutbacks and reduced military spending were announced by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> on Dec. 7, 1988. `` As of today, we have carried out 50 percent of our goal, we have reduced our troops by 256,000 people,'' said <PERSON> Chervov </PERSON>, director of the General Staff. He said there has been an additional reduction of 173,000 military cadets. `` We have substantially reduced major military maneuvers and we are reducing the plans for military materiel and weapons,'' he said. As of Jan. 1, 1990, Soviet troop strength will consist of 3,993,000 soldiers, sailors and airmen, compared to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s 2.2 million military personnel, according to <LOCATION> Chervov </LOCATION>. He did not specify where the cuts were made, but said the reductions were not limited to <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and applied to all branches of the armed forces. <PERSON> Chervov </PERSON> said the 1990 military budget is 70.9 billion rubles -LRB- $ 114.8 billion -RRB-, compared to 77.3 billion rubles for this year. Some of the money slashed from the military budget will be used to convert military production plants into civilian operations to produce more consumer goods, he said, but he gave no figures. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic reforms include increasing consumer goods to alleviate the c