<TEXT>
 A thief who ransacked a house, raided the refrigerator, unwrapped about 40 Christmas presents and made off with some of the gifts apparently had a change of heart. The thief returned the packages the next day with about $ 5 in change and this note: `` Please forgive me. Here are your belongings and some money to fix the window. It may not be enough, but I'll keep bringing some til I pay you back fully. I'm very sorry. Please accept my apology and please do n't send me away.'' <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Shigley </PERSON>, 31, said the presents were found Thursday on her porch by her 10-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, with about $ 5 in nickels and dimes. Mrs. <PERSON> Shigley </PERSON> said the money probably came from a change jar that the thief spilled in the house the day before. The presents were in their original boxes. `` I was amazed. My heart was broke when they all got stolen,'' she said. `` When they came back, I thought, ` Jesus, people really do have a conscience.''' Mrs. <PERSON> Shigley </PERSON> said she may return the favor. `` I thought of leaving a note out there to wish him a merry Christmas and thank him for having a conscience, and I've even thought of leaving a small gift out there for him.'' Her other daughter, <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON>, 12, arrived home from school Wednesday to find the back door window broken. `` Apparently, they came in and made themselves at home. There was cereal and chocolate cookies and cherry pie filling laying out,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Shigley </PERSON> said. She later said she believes only one thief was involved. The presents under the family Christmas tree were unwrapped, and about seven were missing. `` The rest were open for everybody to see,'' she said. `` All my kids know all their surprises.'' <LOCATION> Springdale </LOCATION>, a city of about 23,000 people in the northwestern corner of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, is about 100 miles east of <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla </LOCATION>.
