<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state appeals court has upheld the convictions of a woman who forced her daughter to work as a strip-tease dancer and was prosecuted for child abuse after the girl committed suicide. <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s appeal seeking to overturn her 1987 convictions on charges of child abuse, forgery and procuring a sexual performance by a child was rejected Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Fourth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, altered her daughter's identification before forcing her to get the job dancing nude at an adult club, court testimony showed Her daughter, 17-year-old <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Mancini </PERSON>, shot herself to death in March 1986. Testimony at the subsequent trial showed <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> ordered her underage daughter to perform at nude bars, then collected most of the girl's earnings. No date of surrender has been set yet for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who has been free on $ 4,500 bail, working as a cab driver. She was sentenced in 1987 to 364 days in prison, followed by two years of house arrest and two more years of probation. `` They shoot horses, do n't they?'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said after learning of the appeals court opinion. `` Why do n't they do that with me and get it over with? I wish they would have done it a long time ago.'' The trial was believed to be the first use of a psychological autopsy in a criminal case involving suicide. In rejecting the appeal, the justices approved the use of the evidence in <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s trial `` We are satisfied,'' the justices wrote in their opinion, `` that ... the psychological autopsy is accepted in the field of psychiatry as a method of evaluation for use in cases involving suicide, and that the trial judge acted within his discretion in admitting this evidence at trial.''
