vernment was unconstitutional. <ORGANIZATION> Staten </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islanders </ORGANIZATION> feared that a new government drawn up by a charter revision commission would give them even less power. The secession bill was passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> on the final night of its 1989 session, yet was held back from the governor's desk for several months by <PERSON> Marchi </PERSON> The measure was opposed by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> officials worried about the loss of tax revenue from <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> residents. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> argued that voters in the entire city, not just <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, should vote on secession. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said that there's `` more than enough time'' to deal with the opponents' objections. He did, however, attach one condition to his signature. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he wants new legislation requiring that any new charter that is adopted by <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> voters also be subsequently approved by the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Marchi </PERSON> has agreed to sponsor such legislation next year, said his spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON>. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Mayor-elect <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> has been an integral part of the city since it joined in 1898. `` The law allows the residents of the borough to reconsider this historic relationship,'' <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> said. `` It is my hope that after they complete their evaluation, they will choose to remain part of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s greatest city.'' <LOCATION> 