<HEAD>Memories of the Holocaust</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``The Music Box'' opens in New York and Los Angeles on Dec.
22; ``Enemies, A Love Story'' opened in New York on Dec. 13 and will be
released elsewhere early next year.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three years ago, a friend talked to <PERSON> Constantin </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> about a project concerning <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> permitted to emigrate to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after World War II. The director, who makes films about issues _ Greek political assassination in `` Z,'' Chilean government brutality and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> compliance in `` Missing,'' white extremists in `` Betrayed'' _ was immediately interested. He read books on the subject and developed the idea for his new film, `` Music Box,'' in which a lawyer -LRB- <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> -RRB- defends her Hungarian father against accusations of atrocities committed during the war. `` Essentially, I like to do something which has never been made or said before,'' the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> director explained in a recent interview. `` It's the best way for me to do a movie, to deal with a very original subject. `` We in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> used to think most of the war criminals went to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. When I was in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> they showed me places, ` Here,' ` Here,' ` There,' where Nazis lived. <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> also. In <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, it was quite secret for the general population.'' Memories of the Holocaust also haunt `` Enemies: A Love Story,'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON>'s new film. The director started with <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Beshavis </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>'s novel and filled in his own memories of growing up in the <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> during the 1940s. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Silver </PERSON> stars as <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Broder </PERSON>, a Polish Jew who hid from the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> during the war and now lives in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. He is torn among his current wife, <PERSON> Yadwiga </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> -RRB-, a Polish peasant who took care of him while he hid from the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Masha </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Lena </PERSON> <PERSON> Olin </PERSON> -RRB-, a fellow survivor with whom he's having a passionate affair; and his first wife, <PERSON> Tamara </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Angelica </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> -RRB-, who has returned after supposedly being murdered by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON>, like Singer _ and <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> _ was never in the Holocaust. But `` Enemies'' is simply a story, based on second-hand knowledge and a first-rate imagination, the director insisted. `` <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> spoke to many survivors, I'm sure, who must have flooded the streets of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON>, who also has directed `` <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Tonto </LOCATION>,'' `` An Unmarried Woman'' and `` Down and Out in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>.'' `` He probably got the story from talking to more than one survivor, so that people like <PERSON> Masha </PERSON> and her mother and <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> and the person who hid him in the barn _ those are stories he probably heard and made this tale up. `` I met many survivors, had dinner, conversations, whatever. All that I had gotten I gave to the actors while we rehearsed. I had them meet with some of these people, in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' For `` Music Box,'' Costa-Gavras began with non-fiction and built a story around it. In both films, the Holocaust is always present but never on screen, unlike the recently released `` Triumph of the Spirit.'' For <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON>, the subject seemed too large for even the most learned observer. Singer himself wrote: `` From his -LRB- <PERSON> Herman </PERSON>'s -RRB- own experience with <PERSON> Masha </PERSON> and other survivors of the German camps, he knew that the whole truth would never be learned from those who had survived the concentration camps or the wandering through <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> _ not because they lied but because it was impossible for them to tell it all.'' So <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON> deferred to documentaries such as `` Shoah'' and `` Hotel Terminus'' as more appropriate ways to learn directly about that tragedy. Once research was completed, he concentrated on the actual film. <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> agreed, saying he deliberately confined `` Music Box'' to the present. `` You run the risk of being eaten by the story. In ` Music Box,' there's no particular action, no landscape. It's a very empty movie. It takes place in the present, but with people speaking about the past. How you deal with the past, that's the challenge.'' With such explosive material, it is important to have actors with whom the audience will be comfortable. But balance is necessary; the story always comes first. As <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> noted, `` Music Box'' is not a `` <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON>'' film, any more than `` Missing'' is a `` Sissy Spacek'' film or `` Betrayed'' a `` Debra Winger'' film. `` It's not only being known, it's being a good actor,'' he said. `` You're a good actor and you get known. That's the case with <PERSON> Sissy </PERSON> or Debra or <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemmon </PERSON> and now <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON>. You can spoil the story with a big actor. `` We're far away from the actors of the'40s and the'50s. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>. This is over, those kind of mythical stars. Now we go to see an actor playing a character, a real character. <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> made her character real.'' <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Silver </PERSON>, acclaimed for his performance on stage in `` Speed-the-Plow,'' and said the actor was ideal for playing `` a Herman.'' `` A <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> is somebody who comes from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, whose father was a rabbi, who's a scholar, an intellectual, who loves women, who's very bright, ironic, and who's sad,'' the director explained `` Ron can play that. Certain other actors, a lot of them do n't have all those qualities They'd have to find them. I'm better off finding someone who already has them.'' `` Music Box'' ends with <PERSON> Lange </PERSON>, shattered by what she has learned about her father, embracing her son in back of their lakefront house. With her own innocence gone forever, she can only pass on her knowledge and help her son adjust. `` The theme is about memory,'' <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> said. `` Of course, the memory goes with the future. She does what she does to save her son, to have her son thinking differently and acting differently. To learn how to live with this.'' <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON> adds his own touch at the end of the film, dissolving from a closeup of <PERSON> Yadwiga </PERSON>'s baby to a shot of the <LOCATION> Coney </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> `` Wonder Wheel,'' which can be viewed from <PERSON> Herman </PERSON>'s window. The message is bittersweet: Wounds eventually heal, a new generation is born. But also, the lessons of the Holocaust may be forgotten. `` Out of the baby comes this image of the wheel,'' <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON> said, `` and all through the movie <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> has focused on the wheel in his most contemplative and meditative moments, when he's thinking about God knows what `` The wheel keeps turning, life goes on. The baby is life and life is mysterious. There's man and there's woman, it never ends. Even the Holocaust is absorbed into that circle and the life will go on.''
