<FIRST>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv18   12-15 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 18,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Dec. 18</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Long Dry Spell for Small Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Think big'' has been much more than just a slogan in Wall Street's bull market of the 1980s. Big deals in big stocks have engendered many a big profit. But there was n't much left over for investors in many newer, smaller companies known collectively in the financial world as secondary stocks. So on the verge of the'90s, while owners of blue chips are wondering whether the market can keep on rising, fans of small stocks are asking a more plaintive question: Is their turn ever going to come? Historically, investors who take a chance on smaller stocks have been rewarded with better returns, on average, than those who opted for the presumed safety and stability of household-name companies. <ORGANIZATION> Wright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, investment management firm, says that sine 1950 small stocks have averaged a total annual return -LRB- capital gains plus dividends -RRB- 2.5 percentage points higher than their bigger counterparts, as represented by <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock composite index. When the market began its long advance in the late summer of 1982, that pattern seemed to be holding. So-called `` junior growth'' stocks in technology and other businesses scored some of the standout gains in the first year of the bull market. But around June 1983 they abruptly stalled, and have failed to catch up. `` During the last 6 -LCB- years, investor indifference to small-cap stocks has been virtually unrelenting,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> analysts observed in a recent report. Since mid-1983, they noted, the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 500 has been rolling up an annual return of better than 15 percent a year. Over the same span, the Value Line composite index of nearly 1,700 stocks _ which gives greater weight to a broad array of smaller issues _ has posted an average annual gain of 6.9 percent. That showing failed even to match the 7.2 percent annual return produced by three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, which are considered about the safest, most conservative paper investment available. So investors effectively got paid nothing for taking the considerable risks that come with smaller stocks. Many reasons have been cited for this seeming anomaly, including the predominant influence in the market of investing institutions and foreign investors. Both those groups have a notorious predilection for big-name stocks with large numbers of shares outstanding and high visibility in the marketplace. At the same time, individual investors, who represent a primary constituency of the smaller companies, have been shunning investments in individual stocks, opting instead for mutual funds or other choices far removed from the stock market. It is axiomatic on Wall Street that no trend lasts forever, and this one has gone on for a long time. Small stocks are now `` priced at attractive levels compared to the major market averages,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> says. Despite their subpar showing in recent years, the firm maintains, small companies still hold an edge over bigger ones in their growth potential, since they start from a smaller base and often are run in a more youthful, venturesome spirit. If a bear market develops, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> cautions, it is quite conceivable that neither big nor small stocks will be spared. But the firm concludes that high-quality `` junior blue chips'' are in good position to beat, rather than trail, the big-name stocks over the next five years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
