<HEAD>Mortgage Delinquency Rate Highest in Two Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The delinquency rate for home mortgages jumped sharply to the highest level in more than two years in the July-September quarter, a trade association said. The <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that 5.00 percent of mortgage payments for one-to-four family residences were 30 or more days late, up from a second-quarter rate of 4.52 percent, a 10-year low. It was the highest delinquency rate since the second quarter of 1987, when 5.02 percent of mortgages were past due. A jump in late mortgage payments often reflects economic difficulties among consumers, but <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasko </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> executive vice president, said the association found no ready explanation for the increase. Although economic growth has slowed, the unemployment rate has remained relatively stable, close to 15-year lows, and Americans' disposable personal income grew during the period, he said Historically, the rate sometimes jumps in one quarter only to decline in the next, he cautioned. <PERSON> Lasko </PERSON> noted that the foreclosure rate in the third quarter declined from 1.06 percent to 0.99 percent. Also, the percentages of loans more than 60 days and more than 90 days past due increased only slightly. By region, the 30-day delinquency rate in the Northeast was 4.34 percent in the third quarter, up from 3.74 percent; in the North Central states, 5.13 percent, up from 4.36 percent; in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, 5.53 percent, up from 4.87 percent, and in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, 4.08 percent, up from 3.64 percent. The mortgage survey covers 13 million loans representing $ 597 billion in debt, about one-third of all mortgage loans in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
