<HEAD>Shipment Disruptions Loom After Campeau Says Bankruptcy Filing Possible</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Campeau Glance, BC-Campeau-States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Chetta B'' is cq with no period.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business News</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Suppliers to department stores owned by financially distressed <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> are taking a cautious approach regarding future merchandise shipments. One of the companies that act as middlemen between manufacturers and retailers, known as factors, said Thursday it no longer would extend credit on goods bound for <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s stores. Meanwhile, several apparel and accessory manufacturers said they were keeping in close touch with executives in charge of <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailing operations Bills have been paid on time so far, they said. The suppliers, whose fates are tied to retailers, expressed hope that business would n't be disrupted as <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> copes with a worsening cash shortage. `` I'm very worried about the situation,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, president and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Chetta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> B </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a clothing maker. `` It gets progressively worse looking every day. I'm taking a wait-and-see posture.'' Retail analysts said disclosures by <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of deepening financial difficulties were unsurprising given the fierce competition in the industry. <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> and Allied said in documents submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that their cash could run out by March or sooner and that they might seek protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code. The move would permit Campeau-owned retailers to remain operating while their Canadian parent company sorted out its financial problems. At the heart of the trouble is the massive debt <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> acquired in taking over <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> in 1988 for $ 6.7 billion and Allied in 1986 for $ 3.4 billion. A threatened inability to meet interest payments on junk bonds sold to pay for the acquisitions forced the Toronto-based retail and real estate company to turn to outsiders for help earlier this year. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Olympia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Developments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> came to the rescue with a $ 250 million loan to <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>. As part of a deal for an additional $ 800 million next year from <ORGANIZATION> Olympia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; York, <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> put the <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s department store chain up for sale in September. About a half dozen bidders are evaluating the chain and <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> has said a final sale could be arranged by February. In the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filings, made public Wednesday, <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> and Allied said bankruptcy court protection would be an alternative if lenders wo n't ease repayment terms. <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> owes creditors $ 1.15 billion by the end of April and Allied faces debts of $ 633.7 million due by the end of March. Failing a rescheduling of the payments, <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> said it would consider selling additional holdings, raising money by taking out mortgages on its stores or possibly seeking bankruptcy-court protection. In addition to the 17-store <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s chain, <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> operates <ORGANIZATION> Abraham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Straus </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Burdines </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lazarus </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>'s. Under the Allied umbrella are The <LOCATION> Bon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marche </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marsh </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Maas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brothers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>'s. Combined, the two have about 100,000 employees and 260 stores. Vendors, such as clothing makers <ORGANIZATION> Bernard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chaus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ellen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claiborne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, that do business with many of the stores said they would continue to monitor developments at <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> and that up to now they've been satisfied with how promptly the company has paid for goods. Another yardstick of <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s relationship with vendors could come when some manufacturers seek credit in coming weeks to ship spring merchandise to the stores. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaus </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of the ready-to-wear clothing company that bears his name, said: `` We certainly are going to support them on all fronts.'' <PERSON> Chaus </PERSON> added, however, that he assumes <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> and Allied stores would `` have some major problems with merchandise shipments.'' <PERSON> Chaus </PERSON> does n't use factoring, which involves companies buying accounts receivable and taking over the job of collecting the money due. The second-largest factor in the country, Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Heller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, shut off credit lines to <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> suppliers as of Thursday morning, spokeswoman <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiracek </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> CIT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group-Factoring </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the biggest in the business, said it was continuing to assess the situation. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Basile </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> CIT </ORGANIZATION> unit, said he was concerned there might be an undue reaction in the retail community. He said the only new development was <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s public acknowledgement that bankruptcy-court protection might be necessary. <PERSON> Basile </PERSON> said in an interview that outsiders have thought all along that was a possibility. But, he noted, `` There's a lot of things that we're going to have to resolve before we can approve any future orders.''
