ned $ 2.26 a share in 1988. Those results include a loss of `` a couple of million dollars'' at <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>'s national newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>, in contrast with a loss of about $ 25 million a year earlier, according to <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> Today President <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Curley </PERSON>. He said his aim was to make the newspaper profitable for all of 1990. The company, which owns more than 80 daily newspapers as well as television ands radio stations and an outdoor advertising company, declined to estimate 1990 earnings. Dow Jones, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said it expects to report 1989 earnings per share of $ 3.13 to $ 3.18, up from $ 2.35 a share in 1988. The publisher of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> said that excluding non-recurring gains, its earnings will be off by about 4 percent to $ 1.49 to $ 1.54 a share for the year from $ 1.65 a share a year earlier. Those results have been depressed by losses connected with the foreign exchange trading service operated by its <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> unit and retrenchments in the financial community that have led to sharp declines in financial advertising volume, said Chairman <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, which has properties that include its namesake flagship newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, television stations and cable TV operations, said it expects its earnings per share will rise 20 percent to $ 15.50 from $ 12.90 on a pro forma basis in 1988. It said its operating income will be up 33 percent. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> S