<FIRST>r f PM-SEC-France     12-15 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-France,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC, French Securities Watchdog Sign Cooperation Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and French securities regulators will be exchanging more than pleasantries now that they've signed a new mutual assistance agreement to investigate fraud and other market abuses. Under the agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and its <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> equivalent _ the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> des </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bourse </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- COB -RRB- _ will assist each other by providing information in their respective files, taking statements from individuals and obtaining documents. Both agencies also agreed, in a separate document, to consult each other `` about subjects of common interest in order to coordinate market oversight and resolve differences that may exist'' between the two countries' regualtory system. The agreement was signed Thursday in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> and COB President <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Saint-Geours </PERSON>. In prepared remarks for the signing, released by the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said the agreement provides `` a specific means for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and French regulators to exchange information for use in investigating securities laws violations.'' The statement continued: `` Under the agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> COB </ORGANIZATION> will use their own securities enforcement powers to the greatest possible extent in providing mutual assistance. This will help us to achieve greater stability and integrity in our markets.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investors' transactions in French corporate stock increased from $ 1.2 billion in 1985 to $ 4 billion last year. During the same period, French transactions in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporate stock doubled, from $ 6 billion to $ 12 billion. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> noted that he reached a similar agreement Monday with Dutch securitiees regulators. The statement added that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> has undertaken several moves `` designed to stimulate international capital formation and cross-border activities of securities professionals.'' They include a July regulation easing registration requirements for foreign broker-dealers to conduct some activities in this country; and a new proposal, Rule 144-A, that would facilitate the sale of foreign securities in the private placement market without normal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> registration procedures. `` Even as we eliminate barriers to international securities transactions. we must be alert to the increased risks of cross-border fraud,'' said <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, adding, `` the agreement signed today strengthens our ability to prevent and detect these types of unlawful activities conducted across national borders.'' The agreement allows either <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> or French securities officials to take statements and testimony from individuals in their own country and supply them to the other country's officials. Information supplied to the foreign authorities is to be subject, in most cases, to the confidentiality rules of the supplying country. Unlike the Dutch agreement, the new pact does not confine applicability to French territory in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The agreement, however, limits the exchange of information to events that occurred after the pact goes into effect.
</TEXT>
