<FIRST>r f PM-Xerox-Apple Bjt   12-15 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Xerox-Apple, Bjt,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Xerox Suit Claims Apple Stole Pioneering Machintosh Software Design</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A $ 150 million federal lawsuit alleges <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> employees saw pioneering <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> graphics programs at a trade show in 1981 and pirated the design to create the revolutionary Macintosh computer. The suit, filed Thursday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, also alleges then-Apple President <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Jobs </PERSON> saw a demonstration of another <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> program, Smalltalk, at <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Palo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in 1979, and that he and other <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> employees were `` very impressed with the unique and revolutionary user-friendly design.'' Jobs was ousted from <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 and founded <ORGANIZATION> Next </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes workstation computers. `` <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> never licensed Apple to use the Star computer program or its distinctive graphics or its unique design and appearance or its unique concept and feel,'' the suit said. It also claims <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> gained unauthorized access by hiring several <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> employees in the late 1970s and early 1980s, including Star software developers. The suit, the first of its kind ever filed by <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>, claims <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>'s now-defunct <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> computer system and Macintosh Finder, both copyrighted in 1987, were derived from the two <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> programs. Smalltalk was developed in the mid-1970s, and <PERSON> Star </PERSON> was copyrighted in 1981. The lawsuit says <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> employees saw the Star program at the trade show, in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in June 1981, and copied substantial portions in its <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> and Macintosh Finder programs, including the design and appearance of the main application windows, dialogue boxes and menu, and some of the exact icons, or symbols, used in the program. Apple was granted a license in June 1981 to participate with <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> in a project to implement Smalltalk into a hardware system to be developed by <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>, the suit said. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, Conn.-based <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>, said the civil suit was filed after efforts beginning a week ago to reach an agreement were rebuffed by Apple. `` We sought a settlement with <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> and we resorted to these legal means only when it became absolutely necessary,'' said <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Cupertino </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>'s software graphics concepts are not protected by copyright any more than depictions of birds and trees are protected by the copyright on a painting. `` We believe the case is without merits,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Carleen </PERSON> <PERSON> LeVasseur </PERSON>. `` The complaint confuses the difference between ideas and expression; the copyright protects expresssion, not ideas.'' She said Apple has always recognized <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> and others as responsible for ideas, including computer graphics devices called mirrors and windows. `` Copyright covers artistic expression but not the ideas. In art, it does not cover the trees and birds in a picture, only the picture ... what <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> has done is take those ideas and spend a lot of money in research and development and make our own original expression.'' The suit, which asks for a jury trial, said the Star program `` is widely recognized in the computer industry as being the first to introduce fanciful desktop workstation graphics to allow the user to interact with the computer,'' a development that took <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> `` millions of dollars and years of creative effort.'' The suit claims a total of $ 50 million in damages from unfair competition under state and federal laws, plus punitive damages under state law of an unspecified amount. It also seeks at least $ 100 million from Apple for unjust enrichment from licenses and royalties for its products. Macintosh graphics replaced complicated word codes with simple symbols, vastly streamlining the way users ranging from schoolchildren to office workers select programs, issue commands and perform other functions. In a similar suit, <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> sued <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in the same court in March 1988, claiming infringement of <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> and the Macintosh Finder copyrights, among others, and alleging both were original to Apple. Apple claimed that <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s Windows 2.03 and a <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> program called NewWave, which is based on it, too closely resemble the `` look'' of screen displays on the Macintosh. A federal judge in July issued a tentative ruling that greatly narrowed <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>'s suit by deciding the items covered in a 1985 licensing agreement between <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> could not be used as evidence against <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s and <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION>'s versions of the products.
</TEXT>
