<HEAD>Nikkei Hits New High, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite worries about the almost uninterrupted rise in the market's key index for the past few weeks, share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> posted a new closing high today, while the dollar remained higher in a narrow range. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 90.34 points, or 0.23 percent, to finish the week at a record closing of 38,271.04. The index's previous record closing was 38,180.70 points set Thursday. It breached 38,000 points on Wednesday, when it gained 258.89 points. The market needed only 16 trading days to see the index gain more than 2,000 points. It first rose above 36,000 on Nov. 21. `` Last-minute arbitrage buying by foreign securities firms pushed up the index'' after the Nikkei index generally remained weak throughout the day, <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Bando </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Yamaichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said. An arbitrage deal is a common technique to make profits out of price differentials between the spot and futures markets. The Nikkei index has climbed almost without pause in the last three weeks. <PERSON> Bando </PERSON> said there were some investors taking a cautious attitude over a continued advance in the index, while others were still expected for higher prices ahead. A total of 800 million shares, the same amount traded Thursday, changed hands on the first section. In currency market, the dollar closed at 144.30 yen, up 0.23 yen from Thursday's close of 144.07 yen. After opening at 144.30 yen, the dollar ranged betwen 144.25-144 .38 yen <PERSON> Yoshitsugu </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanada </PERSON>, a dealer with the <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, said the dollar-yen trading was slow the whole day, with many market players awaiting a series of <LOCATION> U