<TEXT>
 As <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock continues to tumble, industry analysts are warning investors not to expect any buyout deal for the airline company to develop soon. `` I suspect it probably will drag on for some time because it's not an easy package to put together,'' analyst <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday, one day after <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s board announced it was still searching for a deal to boost the company's stock Investors registered their disappointment on Wall Street. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, fell $ 5.50 to $ 163.25 a share Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after dropping $ 8 on Wednesday. Nonetheless, airline industry analysts said they were intrigued by the board's statement that it would seek discussions with <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, an investment group that owns an 11.8 percent stake in the company and is pushing for a sale or restructuring. Some said the move could indicate a greater willingess by the board to listen to <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s ideas. But other observers said <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> directors may simply be trying to discern how much clout <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> really carries in its threat to solicit shareholder consents to overthrow <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s board. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> would not comment on when a meeting might be held. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON>, one of <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s general partners, said it was impossible to interpret the board's intentions. But he said <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> was concerned about <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s slow progress in putting together a transaction to increase shareholder value. The New York-based partnership says it will launch its consent solicitation `` if and when we conclude it would be advantageous.'' Airline analysts say <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> probably would have the support of other stock speculators who suffered steep losses on their <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> holdings when a $ 6.75 billion buyout bid by <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots and <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> management collapsed in October. But <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s three general partners are believed to have little desire to actually take control of Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> as they have threatened, since they would then face the same problems that are hampering the current board's efforts to put a deal together. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> management has drafted a new employee-buyout plan that reportedly values the company at $ 240 a share, or $ 5.43 billion, but the proposal has not been endorsed by <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots or flight attendants, and the powerful <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union has said it would oppose such a deal. `` If you're going to have a meaningful <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- employee stock ownership plan -RRB-, you must must have the three unions involved,'' <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON> said. Opposition from the Machinists helped scuttle the $ 6.75 billion pilot-management bid, in which <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> also was to have participated as an equity partner. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attendants </ORGANIZATION> opened a two-day meeting Thursday in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to elect new officers. Local President <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Friend </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> announced earlier this month that they were stepping down, a move expected to reduce friction between management and the flight attendants and perhaps smooth the way toward an employee buyout agreement.
