<HEAD>Guinness Buys Share of Stroh Sparkling Juice Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 British brewing giant <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> says it will tap a fast-growing non-alcoholic beverage market with the purchase of a $ 58 million share of <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s carbonated juice business. The companies said Thursday that creation of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Era </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, in which each will own a 44.5 percent share, is expected to be completed by the end of the year. The joint venture will make and sell <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sundance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Juice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sparklers </ORGANIZATION>. `` In a market that's not growing, we're seeing alcoholic beverage suppliers turn more to non-alcoholic beverages,'' said <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinman </PERSON>, associate publisher of the trade publication Beer Marketer's Insights. New Era's president and chief executive officer will be <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarvie </PERSON>, former chief executive officer of Dr. <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> and of <ORGANIZATION> Schenley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>. Guinness acquired Schenley in 1987. <PERSON> Jarvie </PERSON> will head an investor and management group that will hold the remaining 11 percent of New Era Beverage. Also pending at <LOCATION> Stroh </LOCATION>, the nation's No. 3 brewer behind <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is a September agreement in principle to sell most of its beer brewing and container facilities and brands to No 4 <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 425 million. A definitive agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> is expected early next year, although that transaction has been challenged by smaller brewers as anti-competitive and also awaits <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> review, <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lacey </PERSON> <PERSON> Logan </PERSON> said. The transactions are independent, Stroh Senior Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuehn </PERSON> said. The Coors agreement provides <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> would retain the <LOCATION> Van </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nuys </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, plants that produce Sundance. Guinness already markets non-alcoholic products such as Kaliber lager and <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> malt beverage and wants to expand in that area, said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, a spokesman at the company's <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> headquarters. Sundance has more than 50 percent of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> juice and sparkling water market that is growing at 20 percent a year, <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON> said. Sundance is the only nationally marketed sparkling fruit drink. There are no immediate plans to expand marketing beyond the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON> said. Privately-held Stroh does n't divulge sales or earnings, but analysts estimated 1988 sales at $ 1.4 billion, including $ 75 million to $ 80 million in Sundance sales. Guinness, selling products including <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stout </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dewar </PERSON>'s White Label Scotch whisky, Tanqueray and <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>'s gin and I.W. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> bourbon in 200 countries, had 1988 sales of $ 4.5 billion, <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON> said.
