<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Weather Helps Boost Soybeans; Grains Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean futures prices rose moderately in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, bolstered by cold-weather concerns, but grain futures were mixed. Frigid temperatures in the nation's mid-section have supported the soybean market all week amid perceptions that the cold has boosted demand for soybean meal as a high-energy livestock feed. This morning's temperatures were among the lowest yet this season, with sub-zero readings across <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and much of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The cold snap also supported the corn market, but wheat prices were slightly lower amid profit-taking after moderate gains in the past week. The cold weather was expected to continue for at least another week but analysts said its influence would fade if new export business emerges. `` It's a market that's waiting for more Russian business, that's the best way to characterize it,'' said <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Zusel </PERSON>, manager of <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s floor operations at the Board of Trade In early trading, wheat futures were 1 cent to 1 -LCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in December at $ 4.15 \ a bushel; corn was unchanged to \ cent higher with December at $ 2.35 \ a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to \ cent higher with March at $ 1.55 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were -LCB- cent to 2 -RCB- cents higher with January at $ 5.85 a Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle futures were .10 cent to .22 cent higher with December at 77.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .13 cent lower to .40 cent higher with January at 