<HEAD>GATT Rules EC Soybean Subsidies Unfair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a ruling favorable to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a world trade panel has ruled that <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> subsidies to soybean processors and producers impede trade, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said Friday. The soybean case, one of the main American disputes with the 12-nation European trade bloc, had been portrayed as a test of whether <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> agricultural subsidies generally violate international trade rules. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said a panel set up under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- had ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> soybean subsidies violate <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> rules and impede trade. `` The <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> panel was correct,'' <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said. `` We look forward to the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> correcting the problems that have been identified.'' A <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman confirmed the panel had submitted a report on the dispute and said the parties had 10 days to react. Another <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> source confirmed the report, which was not released publicly, was favorable to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. American soybean producers and exporters complained in 1987 that <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> subsidies nullified or impaired concessions contained in a 1962 trade agreement. Under that pact, the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> allowed duty-free imports of soybeans and other oilseeds in exchange for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tariff concessions. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has claimed that $ 1.5 billion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports have been affected by the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> subsidies policies. <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> officials were not immediately available for comment. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> also criticized aspects of an <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> proposal to reform agricultural trade under the latest round of <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> trade talks. She said the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> proposal to `` rebalance'' its agricultural subsidies by reducing them on some products but increasing them on others `` would not prevent trade distortions, and could reinforce them.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> has proposed replacing agricultural subsidies with more visible and more easily removed tariffs that gradually could be reduced under <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> rules. The <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> has said it would accept some tariffs but oppose eliminating subsidies entirely. Hills is in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> to participate in two days of talks led by Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> is the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' largest trade partner, with $ 190 billion in two-way trade in 1988
