<HEAD>Kodak Says Restructuring To Reduce Earnings $500 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New grafs 1-3 to ADD pretax charges, recast; picks up 3rd graf
pvs bg'ng, Kodak in ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said today its 1989 earnings would be reduced by about $ 500 million because of costs from a restructuring earlier this year. The $ 500 million in net charges for the year translates to about $ 850 million before taxes, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaska </PERSON> said. The photography giant said $ 273 million of the reductions would be charged to fourth-quarter earnings, significantly more than had been anticipated. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> had already charged $ 227 million against earnings for the second quarter and had predicted that the fourth-quarter charge would be lower. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> in August announced a major corporate restructuring that includes between 4,500 and 5,000 job cuts _ about 3 percent of its worldwide work foce _ wage freezes, the sale or consolidation of many businesses and other cost-cutting measures `` This action reflects our efforts to sharpen the focus if the <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> organization by withdrawing from businesses and activities that do not contribute to shareowner value,'' <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> Chairman and Chief Executive <PERSON> Colby </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said in a statement. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said annual earnings would be reduced because of provisions for write-offs of equipment, materials and inventories for various businesses. Additional charges will come from special payment to departing employees. `` Our business units and support organizations are clearly concentrating on value-adding operations and activities,'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>'s statement read. `` As a result, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> will enter the new decade as a stronger, more competitive company.'' <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> earnings have declined in three straight quarters. The Rochester-based company reported a 25 percent third-quarter drop to $ 329 million, or $ 1.02 per share, compared to $ 435 million, or $ 1.35 per share, in the same 1988 quarter. Earnings fell 23 percent in the first quarter and 85 percent in the second quarter compared to year-ago figures. The April-June quarter included expenses of the restructuring. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> has blamed its weakness in part on higher operating costs and no improvement in productivity, deapite strong sales. Net earnings for the first three quarters were $ 589 million, or $ 1.82 a share, down 46 percent from $ 1.09 billion, or $ 3.35 a share, in the first three quarters of 1988. The second-quarter earnings already reflected the $ 227 million in restructuring costs. Sales for the first nine months of the year rose 8 percent to $ 13.5 billion from $ 12.5 billion a year earlier.
