<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices drifted lower in lackluster trading Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with dealers content to follow Wall Street's weak lead. News that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s annual inflation rate rose to 7.7 percent in November from 7.3 percent in October was shrugged off by the market. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended the day 22.3 points, or 0.9 percent, lower at 2,344.7, slightly above its session low of 2,341.5. Volume totaled 444.9 million shares, down from 486.8 million on Thursday. Dealers said volume dropped sharply in the afternoon, when interest evaporated. Despite the market's bearish tone, traders said selective buying helped some shares. The bank sector, in particular, stood out from the rest of the market, although dealers said there were no special reasons for gains there. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 30-share index lost 19.7 points to close at 1,851.7. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 500-share index fell 12.22 points to 1,273.97.
