<FIRST>u f AM-LuxuryPens Bjt   12-15 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Luxury Pens, Bjt,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expensive, Aristocratic Pens May Be The Season's Hottest Gift</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Propelled by the strength of a single human hand, it glides with ease. Its fit feels custom-made. And it's one of the season's hottest selling items: Behold, the pen. But not just any pen. These are luxury pens, the new must-have accessory for the Rolex-watch set. Sales of fine writing instruments are skyrocketing this Christmas, with some retailers reporting increases of up to 70 percent. `` It's incredible,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON>, marketing manager for <PERSON> Waterman </PERSON> pens. `` We can sell every pen we make, and we'll double sales this year.'' Unlike fad gifts of Christmases past _ the pet rock, the Walkman, <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> perfume _ the pen is a time-honored piece. After all, <PERSON> Puccini </PERSON> used a Parker to write <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boheme </ORGANIZATION>, and it was a <PERSON> Waterman </PERSON> that scripted the end of World War I with the signing of the Treaty of <LOCATION> Versailles </LOCATION>. Updated to the'90s, the fancy pen is an affirmation of success. The more aristocratic in design, the better. And the price? It can be anywhere from three figures to four. <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> calls the pen trend a `` cultural phenomenon'' sparked by the growing importance of `` high-quality, functional accessories.'' `` Some people say it's a rebellion against computers,'' said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyers </PERSON>, manager of <ORGANIZATION> Pen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Paper in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION> `` People are tired of everything being faxed and computerized. The art of letter writing is coming back again.'' A fine pen is more than a nostalgic return to personal expression. It is `` a status symbol,'' said <PERSON> Jeannette </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON>, a pen buyer for <ORGANIZATION> Cole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which sells fine pens through its Things Remembered and HQ Gifts stores nationwide. `` Maybe the president -LRB- of a company -RRB- has one, and when he goes to a business meeting, everybody wants to have it,'' she said. Among the growing menagerie of expensive pens, <ORGANIZATION> Cartier </ORGANIZATION>, the master jeweler, is offering its `` Pasha'' fountain pen complete with 40 coats of lacquer and an 18-karat gold nib, or point, for $ 775. Then there's <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s Duofold, a $ 300 pen drilled from a solid block of acrylic, trimmed in 22-karat gold and guaranteed not to explode under airplane pressure. For those seeking something more contemporary, there's the Fendi pen, from the Italian designer of the same name, which is encased in tiny rings of pale gray rubber and sells for a measly $ 35. The year's best seller may be the Montblanc, the product of an 81-year-old West German company. Topped with a signature white `` snowcap'' reminiscent of its namesake, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s highest peak, <ORGANIZATION> Montblanc </ORGANIZATION> pens sell for $ 100 to $ 7,000 each. Retailers say some of <ORGANIZATION> Montblanc </ORGANIZATION>'s success comes from several years of advertising in magazines like <ORGANIZATION> Architectural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Digest </ORGANIZATION>, Vanity Fair and Connoisseur. Now that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s appetite for pens has been whetted, others are riding the wave. <PERSON> Waterman </PERSON>, acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1987, is spending $ 5 million a year to market its French-made writing instruments. The best pens come in ball point, though they are at the lower end of the spectrum. Rollerball pens use liquid instead of paste ink, and therefore are more expensive. The most prestigious is the fountain pen. `` Although the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is a ball-point society, people are finding the enjoyment of going back and writing with a fountain pen,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattes </PERSON>, vice president of marketing for <ORGANIZATION> Koh-I-Noor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapidograph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, the exclusive North American Montblanc distributor. Fountain pens are the fastest growing category of writing instruments. About 12 million were sold in 1987; a year later the number jumped to 21 million. `` If you're going to write a love letter ... does n't it look better with a fountain pen?'' <PERSON> Mattes </PERSON> asked. Because they require special care _ refilling the ink and occasional professional cleanings, fountain pens have a very special cachet. `` You have to have a bit more leisure time to deal with a fountain pen,'' said <PERSON> Waterman </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON>. `` Is n't that the upscale imagery being projected by the user?'' All pens must be chosen carefully. But in the case of a fountain pen, selecting a nib can take hours. Nib widths vary to produce fine to very broad scripts, and the shape of one's penmanship depends on the pressure exterted on the nib and the angle it is held against the paper. Over time, the nib conforms to an individual user, and for that reason, `` one should never lend it,'' <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> said. But despite a luxury pen's ability to elegantly paint words, how they write often is less important than how they look. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s marketing planner <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Watts </PERSON> said one businesswoman told him, `` I do n't use this pen to write with I wear it.''
</TEXT>
