<SECOND>AM-Inflation, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0146,0831</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline Price Drop Pulls Down Overall Wholesale Costs</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS third-to-last graf to CORRECT price index to November sted
October; picks up penultimate graf pvs bg'ng, The inflation ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sharp drop in gasoline costs helped push wholesale prices down in November for the third time in five months, the government said Friday in a report seen as giving the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> leeway to lower interest rates. The annual rate of inflation, as measured by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Producer Price Index, was 4.6 percent for the first 11 months of the year, up from 4 percent for all of 1988 but much lower than was feared earlier this year. The index dipped 0.1 percent last month following a 0.4 percent gain in October and a 0.9 percent spurt in September. It declined 0.5 percent in July and 0.4 percent in August. The roller-coaster ride averages out to an annualized inflation rate of about 1 percent from June through November, a marked contrast to the 9 percent-plus rate for the first five months of the year. `` If ever there was an example of inflation coming in like a lion and going out like a lamb, it was this year,'' said economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities dealer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` That has to be good news for everyone, particularly the consumer.'' Energy prices declined 3.3 percent last month, the sharpest fall since August. A 7.7 percent drop in gasoline prices more than compensated for a 0.1 percent rise in natural gas costs and a 0.7 percent hike in heating oil prices. Analysts credit the taming of inflation to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s tight money policy pursued through this spring As evidence, they cited a separate report by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> on industrial production in November. The operating rate at the nation's factories, mines and utilities eased 0.1 percentage point to 82.7 percent, well below the 10-year high of 84.3 percent at the start of the year, the central bank said. `` Areas that were tight a year ago like chemicals, paper and metals all have excess capacity. When you have excess capacity, you see price concessions,'' said economist <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratajczak </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Since the summer, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has reversed course on monetary policy, hoping to avoid a recession by permitting interest rates to fall. The latest price report gives the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> leeway to cut rates another notch as early as next week, when monetary policy makers gather for the last of their eight annual meetings, economists said. A disappointing trade report for October adds impetus to the push. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the merchandise trade gap soared 19.8 percent to $ 10.2 billion, the highest level in 10 months. A drop in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates could help the deficit by depressing the dollar's value, stimulating exports and discouraging imports. The wholesale price report showed food costs rising a substantial 0.8 percent in November, following a 1.4 percent jump in October, the biggest in 22 months. However, they had declined overall from April through September. Pork prices jumped 7.1 percent following a 9.5 percent rise in October. Prices for turkeys and eggs also rose and dairy prices were up 3.3 percent, the fifth consecutive increase exceeding 1 percent. `` Because of the drought of ` 88, we slaughtered a lot of milk cows and we're starting to see a milk shortage as a result,'' <PERSON> Ratajczak </PERSON> said. `` It's going to take a year to reverse that.'' The increases were partly offset by a 15.1 percent drop in vegetable costs, rebounding from an 18.9 percent rise a month earlier, and a 6.5 percent decline in fresh fruit prices. Prices for fish, chicken, coffee and rice also fell. The price of goods excluding the volatile food and energy categories _ a measure many analysts consider a better gauge of underlying inflationary pressures in the economy _ rose a modest 0.2 percent last month following a 0.1 percent gain in October. Increases for a variety of goods were partly offset by a 4.8 percent decline for soaps and detergents and a 0.3 percent decrease in the passenger car index, which had fallen 1.4 percent in October. Before adjusting for normal seasonal variations, the wholesale price index stood at 114.8 in November. This meant that a hypothetical marketbasket of goods cost $ 114.80 last month compared with $ 109.80 a year earlier. The inflation news was also favorable for earlier stages in the production process. The price of intermediate goods fell 0.1 percent in November after no change a month earlier. Crude-goods prices rose 0.4 percent after holding steady in October. Excluding food and energy, crude goods prices dropped 2.3 percent. An example of the three stages would be bread for finished goods, flour for intermediate goods and wheat for crude goods.
</TEXT>
