<HEAD>Gillette Announes Realignment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, trying to rebuild profits hurt by recent takeover battles, announced Friday it would realign its operations and sell some of its European business, affecting about 750 workers in the process. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> said it was creating a <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shaving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> that would encompass its shaving products and toiletries segments. The reorganization would make the company more efficient, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The move is part of <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy to improve its profits. In recent years, the firm has fended off takeover attempts by <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, but its earnings suffered as a result. This fall, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> said it was introducing a new razor, called Sensor, which would be priced higher than the current brands but also is designed to offer a closer shave. Both the new razor and the new corporate alignment are aimed at improving the company's profits, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fausch </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. `` The company's strategy is to work to increase efficiency, increase profits, increase market share,'' he said. The merging of shaving and personal care will mean the elimination of about 250 jobs, <PERSON> Fausch </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> employs about 29,000 people worldwide. In addition, the company will sell its <ORGANIZATION> Antica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Erboristeria </ORGANIZATION> line of toiletries in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Toja </PERSON> bath products in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, plus European hair care products. Those operations employ about 500 people. Those products have not been as successful as the company had hoped, <PERSON> Fausch </PERSON> said. The operations to be sold represented about $ 100 million in sales last year, compared with about $ 1 billion in worldwide toiletry sales. Proceeds from the sales were expected to offset the costs from the realignment.
