<HEAD>Catalog Companies Touting 11th-Hour Delivery to Hook Christmas Customers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to restores dropped `s' in dwindles; spells out `Maine'
in 3rd graf to conform to style.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the number of days left until Christmas dwindles into single digits, catalog companies are out to persuade last-minute shoppers that they do n't have to brave crowded malls and stores. Guarantees that gifts ordered as late as the week before Christmas will arrive in time to be put under the tree are being touted by catalog companies eager to grab some of the 11th-hour business. Many gift items can be had quickly _ flannel nightgowns from <LOCATION> L.L </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Bean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Freeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, to filet mignons and elegant Beef Wellingtons from <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> Steaks International. The holiday shopping surge does n't flow smoothly between Thanksgiving and Christmas; it typically comes in two big waves at the beginning and the end with a long lull in between. `` We are in the crucial final sprint right now,'' said retail analyst <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc The second wave _ which can make or break the season _ has been a washout for some catalog companies in Christmases past because customers would n't take the risk of being empty-handed on the big day. This year, industry officials guess that possibly more than 150 catalogs are bearing promises that <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parcel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> or other rapid delivery services will speed presents on their way. Some that offered fast delivery in the past have introduced new extras. Sportswear and outdoor gear cataloger Lands' <ORGANIZATION> End </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Dodgeville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, says anything it has in stock can be shipped via <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> to someone's home within two days and the customer can designate the day. A customer who works a standard Monday through Friday week might prefer Saturday delivery, for instance. The cost is $ 6 per address, regardless of the size of the order. Most catalogs boasting fast service require customers to pay a bit more, starting at around $ 4. The charges, which range as high as $ 17.00 an order, could turn off some potential shoppers. But catalogers say they've tried to keep them as low as possible to appeal to procrastinators willing to pay to be spared some aggravation. <ORGANIZATION> Spiegel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which also owns <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> and Honeybee, mailed reminders of its pre-Christmas UPS delivery guarantee to hundreds of thousands of its five million active customers. The guarantee is good for orders placed by Dec. 21, provided the item still is available. It also publicized its holiday program by placing inserts in newspapers around the country and in <LOCATION> Vogue </LOCATION> and GQ magazines. Research done by the <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> brokerage <ORGANIZATION> Blunt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ellis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loewi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> estimated last year's total catalog sales at $ 12 billion. About one-third of all American households bought goods through more than 900 catalogs, <PERSON> Blunt </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> says. Sales through catalogs, which some analysts say have been growing at about twice the pace of store sales in recent years, have expanded to meet the demands of two-income families in which neither parent or spouse has much time to shop. The <ORGANIZATION> Direct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> says that this year 51.4 percent of the adult <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population has ordered at least once by telephone or mail, up from 24.5 percent in 1983, the first year the figures were compiled. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Longendyke </PERSON>, spokesman for <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said express delivery services have made catalogs a more viable method of shopping for people in a hurry, especially ahead of Christmas. `` Before you had to be one of those prudent people that got down to it early,'' he said. `` The great thing now is you can procrastinate without having to go into the stores when they're at their busiest.''
