<HEAD>Chrysler Announces New Incentives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced an incentive program Friday designed in part to maintain production at its two minivan plants before shutting them down to retool for a new version. The program includes a guarantee that the company will make up any difference in rebate programs through the first three quarters of next year _ a time <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has said will include some of the toughest months in recent automotive history. The guarantee is aimed at consumers who may be waiting for more attractive incentives later in the year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Bidwell </PERSON> said Friday at a news conference. `` We want some -LRB- showroom -RRB- traffic now,'' <PERSON> Bidwell </PERSON> said. Sales Manager <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Payne </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Keensport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chrysler-Plymouth </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said his dealership could use some traffic. `` It's real slow this month,'' he said Friday. `` At this time of year, it's hard to compete with <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION>.'' Typically, vehicle sales pick up a little in January and fall off again in February before rebounding in March and April as weather improves. In the past, when one of the Big Three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers issued a new incentive program, the other two soon followed. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had no immediate reaction to <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s move <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s new incentives range from $ 500 to $ 2,000, depending on model, or low-interest financing ranging from 6.9 percent to 9.9 percent, depending on length of loan. Some minivans have an option of cash rebates or interest rates as low as 3.9 percent on a 2-year loan. The program, which expires Jan. 31, 1990, covers two-thirds of the cars and light trucks <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> makes. The incentives on <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s minivans represent the first time in six years that an enticement has been offered on the popular vehicles. Since their introduction, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has commanded more than 50 percent of the minivan market. But that share is being eroded by recent introductions of new minivans from <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and those already in showrooms from <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and a half-dozen or so Japanese companies. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> expects to introduce a new version of its <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caravan </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voyager </ORGANIZATION> next fall for the 1991 model year. Production at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s minivan plants in <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, will be shut down in the third week of June and the third week of July, respectively, to change equipment for the new models. The changeovers will take about four weeks, <PERSON> Bidwell </PERSON> said. Analysts have speculated that automakers, faced with swelling inventories and waning demand, may cut their supplies of unsold cars by curtailing production during the first quarter of 1990. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said this week that it would shut down its car plant near <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, causing about 3,400 layoffs, for four weeks beginning Monday because of slow sales of the Chrysler LeBaron and the <LOCATION> Dodge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION>. The company also said 3,000 employees of its <LOCATION> Belvidere </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, plant, which makes five full-size cars, would be laid off for two weeks beginning Jan. 2 because of falling sales. <PERSON> Bidwell </PERSON> said that wo n't be the case for <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s minivan plants, which make a product that's responsible for much of the company's shrinking profits. `` We absolutely do not face downtime except for the changeover,'' <PERSON> Bidwell </PERSON> said. However, he added, some overtime at the two plants may be cut. Analysts and industry officials have agreed that demand for minivans will remain strong during next year while the industry as a whole weakens. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has forecast that 14.2 million cars and light trucks will be sold in 1990, down from the 14.8 million or so that will be sold this year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has forecast a slightly slower year in 1990 while <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has forecast the industry will sell 15 million vehicles.
