<HEAD>Knight-Ridder, Tribune Co., NY Times Co. Discuss Earnings Outlooks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Media giant <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it expects to post higher earnings this year and that savings from its recently-enacted newspaper joint operating agreement in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> will boost 1990 earnings. <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, said it expects a profit increase for 1989 but said earnings growth would be more difficult to achieve in 1990 due to impending labor negotiations, slow advertising revenue growth and weak newsprint prices. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said a gain on the sale of its cable operations would mean record 1989 earnings, but earnings from continuing operations _ excluding the cable sale gain _ would be down substantially. It expects higher earnings in 1990 excluding the cable sale gain. The companies discussed their earnings prospects before securities analysts attending the annual <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> media outlook conference. Advertising revenue growth from Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s 29 daily newspapers, lower newsprint prices and lower interest costs were cited for contributing to the company's stronger 1989 earnings outlook. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Batten </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive, declined to offer a specific projection of earnings. But securities analysts have estimated 1989 earnings per share from continuing operations will amount to between $ 2.80 and $ 2.90 compared with net income of $ 2.59 a share in 1988 and 1990 earnings per share from continuing operations of $ 3.40 to $ 3.50. <PERSON> Batten </PERSON> said one major contributor to earnings growth in 1990 would be the recent enactment of the joint operating agreement between <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc He said the agreement, which combined business operations of the newspapers while news and editorial staffs operate separately, means an end to 11 consecutive years of operating losses at the Free Press. <PERSON> Batten </PERSON> said the Free Press was expected to lose between $ 13 million and $ 16 million in 1989, excluding corporate charges but that the company `` wo n't lose money in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> next year.'' <PERSON> Batten </PERSON> said the end of losses at the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> newspaper, contiunued soft newsprint prices, improvement at The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> and strong results from business information services will help 1990 earnings. Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said strong growth in its broadcasting and entertainment businesses as well as increases from newspapers should help it post earnings per share of $ 3.10 in 1989, up from $ 2.78 in 1988. But <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, senior vice president and chief financial officer, although the company would like higher earnings per share in 1990, `` this may be a difficult goal to achieve.'' He said the company faces `` difficult labor negotiations'' involving workers at the Daily News in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He said contract talks also will occur next year involving newsprint production workers in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and major league players. <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> owns the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> baseball team. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said newspaper ad revenues were up 4.5 percent to 5 percent in 1989 and should be slightly higher in 1990. But he said weakness in newsprint prices may persist, hurting <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>'s results from newsprint operations. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 2.08 a share in 1988 and posted a gain of $ 2.46 per share this year on the sale of its cable system. It announced earlier this week it intended to charge 57 cents a share against fourth-quarter earnings, reflecting estimated costs of voluntary staff cuts at its flagship newspaper due to a weak advertising climate in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, further automation of production facilities and a decline in its valuations of its investment in forest products operations. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON>, president and chief operating officer, said a 7 percent decline in ad linage at the Times offset the effects of tighter cost controls. That combined with lower newsprint prices in 1989 will produce flat operating results from newspapers, excluding special charges taken in 1988. He said results from magazines would decline from 1988, showing a loss for the year due to acquisitions, but that broadcast and information services were up and regional newspapers had a record year. Newsprint business results also are down sharply, he said. <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON> said with the charges, the company lost money in the fourth quarter and that earnings from continuing operations `` will be down substantially for the year.'' Including the cable gain, however, the company will have record earnings for the year. He said he agreed with analysts who have predicted `` another year of low earnings'' in 1990 but said earnings should top 1989 results, excluding the cable sale.
