<HEAD>GM, Saab In Auto Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> will buy half of <ORGANIZATION> Saab-Scania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION>'s troubled car business for about $ 600 million, in a deal analysts described Friday as a good one for both companies. The analysts' endorsement of the association is far different from the concern some voiced seven weeks ago when <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced it would buy all of British automaker <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> for $ 2.5 billion. `` <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> paid about $ 3,000 per unit and <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> went for about $ 40,000 per unit,'' said analyst <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Merlis </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, referring to the ratio of investment price and the sales of <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> cars. `` One way to look at the $ 600 million is that's how much it takes to build a new car,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> will form a new independent Swedish car company called <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION> which will produce cars under the <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> name for worldwide distribution and some <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> models for the European market. In <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Saab-Scania </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Georg </PERSON> <PERSON> Karnsund </PERSON> said in a statement that times are tough for low-volume automakers. <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>'s car operations lost $ 186.1 million during the first eight months of this year `` Soaring costs for research and development and ever-increasing international competition make it difficult for small-volume makers to survive on their own in a longer perspective,'' he said. `` For <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>,'' said analyst <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, `` I think there are some definite benefits. They get greater access to the Scandinavian market and the European market in general. `` The days of the smaller, niche-oriented companies are getting fewer and farther between,'' he said. Under their agreement, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> will invest $ 100 million in the new venture. Each company will nominate five members of the 10-member board, and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> will nominate the chairman. The company will manufacture and distribute cars under the <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> name for sale through <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>'s independent dealer network and produce <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> cars for sale through <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> organization, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. `` Saab products are considered a premium brand. They have a good image for high technology and performance,'' said <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Harned </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. Also under the agreement, <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> will form a new <ORGANIZATION> Saab-Scania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION>, in which <ORGANI