<HEAD>Coors-Stroh Letter of Intent Expires With No Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A letter of intent for <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to buy <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic beer making operations for $ 425 million expired Friday with no sale, freeing <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> to seek other buyers, the companies said. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Sortwell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> vice president for corporate planning and development, said the companies agreed not to discuss details, such as whether the price or antitrust considerations were stumbling blocks to the buyout. But Coors President <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON> cited unresolved issues in the transaction as originally contemplated and concern with antitrust issues. `` We felt it best for both parties to take a fresh look at things and explore other alternatives,'' he said. <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> Chairman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> said his company expects to continue discussions with <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>, although on terms different from those in the letter of intent. <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> also will consider discussions with others, he said. `` Apparently they have opened up the negotiations to anyone,'' said <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, beverage analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It does sound like the deal is off. I think they must have disagreed on price,'' <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> officials would n't discuss whether others have made overtures, <PERSON> Sortwell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> has argued that c