<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower In Thin Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished mostly lower Friday in dealings that remained thin despite the release of key economic data. Gold prices gained more than $ 5 an ounce, mostly on speculative buying. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery rose $ 5.60 a troy ounce to settle at $ 413.90. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> quoted a late bid for gold even higher at $ 414.50 an ounce, up $ 6.20 from Thursday's late bid. The government's latest reports on the economy proved bearish for the dollar. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit widened to $ 10.2 billion in October, greater than the $ 9 billion traders had expected. A large deficit makes a case for a lower dollar, which helps improve the trade gap by making imports more expensive and exports cheaper. Separately, the government said producer prices slipped 0.1 percent in November, bucking predictions that called for a 0.1 percent gain. After the figures were released, `` the dollar came off fairly substantially,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrissey </PERSON>, senior trader at the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office. The dollar fell below the critical 1.7210 level against the West German mark, leading traders to believe the currency is gathering momentum to move lower. News of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> declaring that a `` state of war'' exists with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> helped the dollar strengthen a bit and gave gold prices a boost. But another mild tremor shook the currency market late in the session when the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was briefly down 45 points. The dollar finished at lower levels in sparse trading. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose 0.23 Japanese yen to a closing 144.30 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 144.10 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar closed at 144.15 yen, unchanged from late Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound rose to $ 1.6055 from $ 1.5970 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> one pound cost $ 1.6030, more expensive than Thursday's $ 1.6010. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday, included: 1.7190 West German marks, down from 1.7344; 1.5480 Swiss francs, down from 1.5630; 5.8785 French francs, down from 5.9285; 1,283.50 Italian lire, down from 1,292.50, and 1.1608 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1598. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday, included: 1.7225 West German marks, down from 1.7375; 1.5485 Swiss francs, down from 1.5630; 5.8885 French francs, down from 5.9420; 1.9480 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9565; 1,286.50 Italian lire, down from 1,295.75, and 1.1606 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1585. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 412.25 a troy ounce from $ 407.50 bid late Thursday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, the metal rose to a closing bid of $ 412.50 from $ 408.50 bid late Thursday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 65 cents to close at a bid $ 409.30. Silver rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 5.62 a troy ounce from $ 5.58 bid late Thursday. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery finished at $ 5.607 an ounce, up from Thursday's $ 5.557.
