<FIRST>u f AM-Kodak     12-15 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kodak,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Puts 1989 Restructuring Costs at $500 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that costs related to a restructuring announced this year would reduce fourth quarter earnings by $ 273 million, significantly more than the company had predicted. The $ 273 million charge brings <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s total 1989 restructuring costs to $ 500 million, or $ 850 million before taxes, spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaska </PERSON> said. The photography giant had charged $ 227 million against its second quarter earnings. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> had estimated earlier this year that fourth quarter charges would be lower than those in the second quarter. `` Charges have evolved as plans have finalized,'' <PERSON> Kaska </PERSON> said. `` It's the difference between predictions and actual experience.'' <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> has now accounted for all charges associated with the restructuring, <PERSON> Kaska </PERSON> said. `` Charges in 1990 should be only those that occur in the normal course of our ongoing operations,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> announced a restructuring plan in August designed to save the company $ 1 billion in costs and turn around its sagging profits. The plan includes selling or reorganizing about 20 businesses and cutting more than 4,500 jobs _ about 3 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s worldwide workforce _ as well as freezing wages and other cost-cutting measures. `` This action reflects our efforts to sharpen the focus of the <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> organization by withdrawing from businesses and activities that do not contribute to shareowner value,'' Chairman and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Colby </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. `` Our business units and support organizations are clearly concentrating on value-adding operations and activities,'' he said. `` As a result, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> will enter the new decade as a stronger, more competitive company.'' <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> earnings have declined in three straight quarters. The Rochester-based company has blamed its poor showing on higher operating costs and no improvement in productivity, as well as competition from abroad. Earnings dropped 25 percent in the third quarter to $ 329 million, or $ 1.02 a share, vs. $ 435 million or $ 1.35 per share in the same 1988 quarter. Earnings fell 23 percent in the first quarter and 85 percent in the second quarter, when the first restructuring charges were recognized. Net earnings for the first three quarters were $ 589 million, or $ 1.82 a share, down 46 percent from $ 1.09 billion, or $ 3.35 per share, in the first three quarters of 1988. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Obenzinger </PERSON>, a stock analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Trinity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, predicted that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> would do no better than break even in the fourth quarter of 1989. Earnings in 1990 will improve simply because there will be no more charges, he said, but <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> will face a number of challenges to improving profits in the first half of the year. Among those challenges is the expected ruling on how much <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> will have to pay <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> for violating its instant camera patent _ predicted to be in the $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion range. The company also faces fierce foreign competition and a weak economy, <PERSON> Obenzinger </PERSON> said. `` As you go into the first quarter of 1990 it's going to be a fairly interesting time,'' he said. `` This addresses the ills of the past but does not guarantee them the future.'' <PERSON> Kaska </PERSON> said slightly more than a third of the $ 500 million charge reflects inventory writeoffs from the businesses <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> is exiting. Other costs include writeoffs of equipment and goodwill costs _ the amount a company pays for an asset in excess of its value, and benefits paid to departing employees, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> has so far announced the sale of 10 businesses, and <PERSON> Kaska </PERSON> said the company hopes to have the sale of at least 10 more completed in the next two weeks.
