<HEAD>Bonds Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices were mostly lower Friday as traders had little response to government data giving further mixed signals on the economy. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-year bond fell 1-32 point, or less than $ 1 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield was unchanged from late Thursday at 7.85 percent. Analysts said the credit markets shrugged off a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report that the nation's merchandise trade deficit soared to $ 10.2 billion in October, a 19.8 percent jump from September's $ 8.51 billion imbalance. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Producer Price Index dipped 0.1 percent last month following a 0.4 percent gain in October and a 0.9 percent rise in September. Analysts said the producer-price index figure was better than expected while the trade deficit growth was worse. The reports negated each other in impact on the credit markets. `` The general gist of all the evidence we've had over the entire week is that we have a pretty sluggish situation in the conomy,'' said <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` But there was nothing either great or harmful to get things moving,'' she said. `` The market is very quiet. There are n't that many positions in the Street now.'' Bondholders have welcomed recent news of a slowing economy because it implies less demand for goods and services, easing the risk of inflation, which erodes the value of bonds. Slower growth also encourages the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to take steps that would lower interest rates to stimulate the economy. Lower rates make fixed-income investments such as bonds more valuable. Economists said they believe the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> could ease interest rates next week. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities, prices of short-term issues were down 1-32 point to 1-16 point, intermediate-term maturities were 1-16 point to 3-32 point lower, and long-term issues were unchanged to down 1-32 point, according to figures provided by <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial information service. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, was down 0.34 at 1,195.65. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills rose to 7.88 percent as the discount gained 2 basis points to 7.64 percent. Yields on six-month bills rose to 7.78 percent while the discount rose 1 basis point to 7.40 percent. Yields on one-year bills issued at auction Thursday were at 7.63 percent with the discount off 1 basis points to 7.13 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face value, paid at maturity. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted at 8 -LCB- percent, down from 87-16 percent late Thursday. In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively traded municipal bonds closed at 93 23-32, up 1-32 point. The average yield to maturity was unchanged at 7.24 percent.
