<HEAD>NASD Fines Brokerage $100,000 For Crash-Related Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The brokerage firm <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to pay a $ 100,000 fine and be censured for stock pricing violations following the 1987 market crash, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. In addition, <PERSON> Prudential-Bache </PERSON> `` made adjustments'' of $ 235,901.50 in the prices customers paid in connection with the questioned transactions, the association said in a statement. In settling the matter, <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> neither admitted nor denied the allegations, the statement said. The association's market surveillance committee said <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> received sell orders involving 20 securities for which it was the market maker on Oct. 19, 1987, but failed to complete the sales while the market was open. It said the firm subsequently bought the securities from the customers at prices that were at least 8 percent below the lowest reported price of the day. As a result, the committee said the 186 customer accounts placing the sell orders received $ 235,901.50 less than what they would have received had the orders been executed at the lowest price of the day. The allegations involve activities on Black Monday when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average plunged 508 points in its biggest one-day loss ever. <PERSON> Prudential-Bache </PERSON> was unable to execute the trades until after the close of the market because of the extraordinary market conditions. But the association said that the firm had access before it made the deals to information that indicated the intra-day trading range for these securities. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> is a self-regulatory organization for the over-the-counter markets. Its surveillance committee is responsible for maintaining the integrity of those markets.
