<HEAD>Phoenix Corporation Announces Loss, New Debt Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Debt-ridden <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> K </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Friday reported that it has arranged short-term debt relief in an attempt to get ahead of its interest payments. Company spokesman <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said the new agreement was made possible when a syndicate of banks waived compliance with the required-profit-level covenants covering Circle K's $ 325 million credit agreement. The company has drawn on $ 260 million, <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> said. In addition, Circle K received a $ 60 million, 100-day extension of credit, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> also announced a $ 4.99 million loss, amounting to 16 cents per share, for the second quarter of its 1990 fiscal year. In the Aug. 1-Oct. 31 period, Circle K had revenues of $ 937.2 million, <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> said Last year, the company reported a $ 13.30 million profit, or 25 cents per fully diluted share, on sales of $ 851.67 million. Part of the loss stemmed from a $ 2.2 million charge in the company's failed attempts to find a buyer for itself. Circle K began the effort in May and abandoned it several months ago after Chairman <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Eller </PERSON> decided not to bid on a buyout. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> added that the operating results also included an after-tax loss of just over $ 1 million for its 50 percent share of a joint venture in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>'s secretary said he was unavailable for comment on the status of the corporation, which last month announced a restructuring that includes refinancing of debt, a salary freeze, layoffs and the sale of up to 590 stores deemed unprofitable. On Dec. 7, Circle 7 announced a Dec. 15 deadline to get ahead of its debt service with $ 20 million in credit. It said the banks which are part of its revolving-credit agreement agreed to make $ 10 million available, and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, Circle K's largest stockholder, agreed to advance the same amount. The new agreement includes the banks, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> and `` certain issuers of letters of credit -LRB- which -RRB- ... have consented to refrain from taking actions to reduce their extensions of credit during the term of the short-term agreement,'' <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said in his statement. The covenants apply to $ 200 million in senior secured notes due Oct. 15, 1993. They require Circle K to maintain at the end of each quarter a minimum fixed-coverage ratio for the preceding 12 months, <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Funds to make such payment are not presently available to the company,'' <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> said. He said failure to meet the profit levels or negotiate the agreement struck late Friday would have forced the company to buy back $ 20 million of the long-term debt. According to company figures, <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> K </ORGANIZATION> has long-term debt of about $ 1.1 billion, up from $ 844 million the year before, and paid $ 96 million in interest and debt expenses during the 1989 fiscal year. The company's financial woes followed explosive expansion which saw Circle K grow from about 1,000 convenience stores in 1984 to a high of 4,685. The financial statement Friday said the total had dropped to 4,677. The company owns about 12 percent of the stores; the others are franchised.
